(103, 179, 'Laura Dck', 'Corse, France', 'French English', '<p data-start=\"74\" data-end=\"89\"><strong>Laura Dck</strong><br><strong>Representative Corse</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"91\" data-end=\"369\">Ferue de randonnÃ©e et installÃ©e en Corse, jâ€™ai dÃ©couvert le NÃ©pal grÃ¢ce Ã  Mingmar Sarkee Sherpa, fondateur de lâ€™agence Lhakpa Trekking. DÃ¨s mon premier trek, il mâ€™a fait vivre une expÃ©rience inoubliable, guidÃ© par la passion, la bienveillance et un profond sens du partage. Mingmar est un guide exceptionnel qui porte haut des valeurs humaines fortes, quâ€™il transmet aussi Ã  travers sa fondation, Å“uvrant pour lâ€™Ã©ducation dans les rÃ©gions reculÃ©es de lâ€™Himalaya et le travail des femmes au NÃ©pal. Je suis fiÃ¨re de le soutenir et jâ€™ai dÃ©jÃ  hÃ¢te de repartir sur les sentiers Ã  ses cÃ´tÃ©s.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"690\" data-end=\"728\">ğŸ“§E-mail : .....................................................<br data-start=\"710\" data-end=\"713\">ğŸ“ PhoneWhatsApp : +33 6 75 97 37 62</p>', '1753952164.jpeg', 25, 'Dr-Laura-Dck-', '1753952164576', 1, 1, '2025-07-31 18:41:04', '2025-12-15 18:51:01'),
(104, 179, 'Karin Hoarau', 'RÃ©union - France', 'French', '<p data-start=\"116\" data-end=\"134\"><strong>Karin Hoarau</strong><br><strong>Representative RÃ©unionÂ </strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"136\" data-end=\"459\">Originaire de lâ€™Ã®le de La RÃ©union, petit joyau franÃ§ais de lâ€™ocÃ©an Indien, nous sommes fiÃ¨res de soutenir Lhakpa Trekking. Au-delÃ  de notre soutien Ã  Mingma Sarkee Sherpa et son entreprise, nous partageons profondÃ©ment leur mission, humaine et inspirante.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"136\" data-end=\"459\">Nous avons eu la chance de dÃ©couvrir le NÃ©pal Ã  travers les yeux de Mingma et de ceux qui Å“uvrent pour un tourisme respectueux, authentique et porteur de sens.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"136\" data-end=\"459\">Si vous rÃªvez dâ€™un voyage au NÃ©pal, chez Lhakpa Trekking, vous ne serez pas de simples voyageurs : vous serez des partenaires dâ€™une aventure humaine. Chaque randonnÃ©e est une immersion dans une culture fascinante, tout en contribuant Ã  un projet plus grand : lâ€™autonomisation des femmes, lâ€™accÃ¨s Ã  une Ã©ducation de qualitÃ© dans les rÃ©gions reculÃ©es, et le dÃ©veloppement dâ€™un tourisme professionnel, responsable et durable.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"792\" data-end=\"830\">ğŸ“§ Email: .......<br data-start=\"812\" data-end=\"815\">ğŸ“ Phone: ......</p>', '1754377444.jpeg', 26, '-Karin-Hoarau', '1753952612822', 1, 0, '2025-07-31 18:48:32', '2025-12-15 18:51:29'),
(105, 179, 'Henry Fabienne', 'Bretagne, France', 'French', '<p data-start=\"116\" data-end=\"134\"><strong>Henry Fabienne</strong><br><strong>Representative Bretagne, FranceÂ </strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"yiv1459409221MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">I am a university professor based in Brittany, France, with a deep passion for the natural world and high-altitude adventures. My love for the Himalayas has led me to Nepal many times, even during the monsoon season, where Iâ€™ve pursued my dreams of exploring its remote beauty and rich cultural landscapes.</p>\r\n<p class=\"yiv1459409221MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mingmar was our guide on a trek around the AnnapurnasÂ : a magnificent encounter, the foundation of a solid and lasting friendship and of very beautiful humain expÃ©riences. He is what we call a Â«Â beautiful personÂ Â», carrying deeply rooted humanist values both in his professional practice and in his personal life. Among other commitments he actively works to preserve and perpetuate the Sherpa CultureÂ ; through our associations Nepal Care Concern and Terre dâ€™Espoir Armor,he works with great energy to promote access to school for all children in remote mountain villages.</p>\r\n<p class=\"yiv1459409221MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The experiences he offers you are just like him. So if you share a similar passion for nature and adventure, values of sharing and respect, feel free to reach out - Iâ€™d be happy to offer insights or ideas to help you fulfil your himalayan dream.</p>\r\n<p class=\"yiv1459409221MsoNormal\">Â </p>\r\n<p data-start=\"792\" data-end=\"830\">ğŸ“§ Email: fabienne.henry@gmail.com<br data-start=\"812\" data-end=\"815\">ğŸ“ Phone: +33 6 84 78 06 04</p>', '1754378807.jpg', 27, 'Henry-Fabienne', '1754378807885', 1, 0, '2025-08-05 17:11:47', '2025-12-15 19:03:21'),
(106, 215, 'Prem Sherpa', 'Korea', 'Korean English', '<p data-start=\"102\" data-end=\"201\"><strong data-start=\"102\" data-end=\"149\">Representative in Korea</strong><br data-start=\"149\" data-end=\"152\"><em data-start=\"152\" data-end=\"201\">Former English-speaking mountain guide in Nepal</em></p>\r\n<p data-start=\"203\" data-end=\"479\">After many years of guiding in the majestic Himalayas of Nepal, I was given the opportunity to come to Korea for a professional assignment. I will be here for a couple of years before returning to my homeland, where I will proudly continue my passionate work in the mountains.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"481\" data-end=\"668\">If you\'re dreaming of a journey to Nepal for your next vacation, feel free to reach out with any questions. It would be our pleasure to share our experience and help guide your adventure.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"670\" data-end=\"725\"><strong data-start=\"670\" data-end=\"677\">NB:</strong> Queries are welcome in both Korean and English.</p>', '1757754264.JPG', 28, 'korea', '1754383933720', 1, 1, '2025-08-05 18:37:13', '2025-12-15 18:58:32'),
(108, 171, 'Mt Everest', '(1st) Elev. 8848.86 m | Nepal-China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mount Everest (8,848.86 m), located on the border of Nepal and Tibet (China) in the Himalayas, was first measured in 1856 during the Great Trigonometric Survey of India as Peak XV and named after Sir George Everest in 1865. British climbing attempts began in the 1920sâ€“30s, including the 1924 Malloryâ€“Irvine expedition. The first confirmed ascent was on May 29, 1953, by Sir Edmund Hillary of New Zealand and Tenzing Norgay Sherpa of Nepal. China achieved the first north-side ascent in 1960, and in 1975 Junko Tabei of Japan became the first woman to summit. Since then, climbers from around the world have set records, with Sherpas playing a vital guiding role.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"773\" data-end=\"1196\">As of December 2024, 7,269 individuals have reached the summit, with 12,884 total ascents. Each year, 700â€“1,000 climbers attempt the mountain, with a 60â€“70% success rate. Locally, it is known as Sagarmatha (Nepali, â€œForehead of the Skyâ€), Chomolungma (Tibetan, â€œGoddess Mother of the Worldâ€), and Qomolangma (Chinese). Today, Everest stands as a global symbol of challenge, courage, and adventure.</p>', '1756878914.jpg', 1, 'Test-', '1756795988761', 1, 0, '2025-09-02 16:38:08', '2025-09-07 12:44:49'),
(109, 171, 'Mt.K2', '(2nd) Elev.  8,611 m | Pakistan - China', NULL, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">K2 (8,611 m), also known as Mount Godwin-Austen, is the worldâ€™s second-highest mountain. It is located in the Karakoram Range on the border of Pakistanâ€™s Gilgit-Baltistan and Chinaâ€™s Xinjiang. In Balti, it is called Chogori, meaning â€œGreat Mountainâ€ or â€œKing of Mountains.â€ The name K2 was introduced in 1856 by British surveyor Thomas Montgomerie during the Great Trigonometric Survey of India, identifying it as the second Karakoram peak.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nicknamed the â€œSavage Mountain,â€ K2 is notorious for its difficulty, harsh weather, and high fatality rate. Early 20th-century expeditions failed, but on July 31, 1954, Italians Achille Compagnoni and Lino Lacedelli, led by Ardito Desio, made the first ascent. With no easy route, all approaches are technically demanding, and it is climbed far less often than Everest, widely regarded as the ultimate mountaineering challenge.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Local names: Chogori (Balti), K2 (survey name, 1856), Mount Godwin-Austen (rarely used).</p>', '1756878838.jpg', 2, 'Mt-K2', '1756878324951', 1, 0, '2025-09-03 15:30:24', '2025-09-07 12:45:47'),
(110, 171, 'Kangchenjunga', '(3rd) Elev. 8,586 m |  Nepal - India', NULL, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">Kangchenjunga (8,586 m)</span>, the worldâ€™s third-highest mountain, lies on the border of Nepal and India (Sikkim) in the Himalayas. Its Tibetan name, <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">Kangchen DzÃ¶-nga</span>, means â€œFive Treasures of the Great Snow,â€ referring to gold, silver, gems, grain, and holy books believed to be hidden in its five peaks. Revered as sacred in Sikkimese culture, it is considered the abode of the gods, and climbers traditionally avoid stepping on the very summit.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"562\" data-end=\"1012\">First surveyed by the British in the mid-19th century, Kangchenjunga proved difficult due to its remoteness, steep terrain, and severe weather. On <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">May 25, 1955</span>, a British expedition led by <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">Charles Evans</span> achieved the first ascent, with <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">Joe Brown</span> and <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\'; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">George Band</span> reaching the summit but stopping short to respect local beliefs. Today, Kangchenjunga remains one of the most remote, sacred, and technically demanding peaks in the world.</p>', '1756881901.jpg', 3, 'Kangchenjunga-8586-m-', '1756881901576', 1, 0, '2025-09-03 16:30:01', '2025-09-07 12:46:40'),
(111, 171, 'MT. Lhotse', '(4rth) Elev.  8,586 m | Nepal - Tibet (China)', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Lhotse (8,516 m), the worldâ€™s fourth-highest mountain, lies on the Nepalâ€“Tibet (China) border, just south of Everest. Its Tibetan name means â€œSouth Peak,â€ reflecting its position as part of the Everest massif, connected via the South Col. Known for the steep and difficult Lhotse Face, it is regarded as one of the most demanding Himalayan peaks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"449\" data-end=\"852\">First surveyed in the mid-19th century during the Great Trigonometric Survey of India, it was first climbed on May 18, 1956, by Swiss climbers Ernst Reiss and Fritz Luchsinger. By March 2012, Lhotse had seen 461 successful ascents (371 by 2008), with no summits between 2014 and 2016 due to accidents. The most recent ascent was in May 2025 by Lin Zhiyong and Dipan Gurung.</p>', '1757310270.JPG', 4, 'Kangchenjunga-8586-m-', '1756881938765', 1, 0, '2025-09-03 16:30:38', '2025-09-08 15:29:30'),
(112, 171, 'MT. Makalu', '(5th) Elev. 8,481 m | Nepal - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Makalu (8,481 m) is the fifth-highest mountain in the world, situated on the Nepal and China border. Its name is derived from the Sanskrit term â€œMaha Kala,â€ meaning â€œGreat Black Mountain.â€ Makalu was first ascended in 1955 by the French climbers Jean Couzy and Lionel Terray. The mountain is renowned for its pyramidal shape, sharp ridges, and steep faces, making it one of the most technically challenging peaks in the world. Located approximately 19 km southeast of Mount Everest, Makalu remains remote, pristine, and less frequently climbed.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Makalu is one of the most challenging 8,000-meter peaks, with a general success rate of around 9% (2012 NASA data). By 2022, there were 206 successful ascents. In the Spring 2025 season, the route opened on April 10, and teamsâ€”including an Indian ITBP group and an Australian climberâ€”reached the summit in mid-April and early May.</p>', '1757310446.jpg', 5, '-Mount-Makalu', '1756974389866', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 18:11:29', '2025-09-08 15:32:26'),
(113, 171, 'MT. Cho Oyu', '(6th) Elev. 8,188 m | Nepal - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cho Oyu (8,188 m) is the sixth-highest mountain in the world, located on the Nepalâ€“China border. The local name of Cho Oyu is â€œChowang YÃ¼â€ in Tibetan, which means â€œTurquoise Goddess.â€ It was first climbed in 1954 by Herbert Tichy, Joseph JÃ¶chler, and Pasang Dawa Lama. Cho Oyu is known for its gentler slopes, making it one of the more accessible 8,000-meter peaks, though it remains challenging due to altitude and weather. It is situated west of Mount Everest in the Himalayas.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are no exact statistics on failed Cho Oyu attempts, but it has over 3,800 successful summits. In recent years, higher permit costs, Chinese visa difficulties, and the challenging south-face route have made climbs harder, especially after the Covid-19 pandemic. It has a low death-to-summit ratio compared to other 8,000-meter peaks. The most recent notable climb was the first recorded summit from the Nepalese side in June 2024</p>', '1757310724.jpg', 6, 'MT-Cho-Oyu-', '1756974585765', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 18:14:45', '2025-09-08 15:37:04'),
(114, 171, 'Mt.Dhaulagiri I', '(7th) Elev. 8,167 m|Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dhaulagiri, the seventh-highest mountain in the world at 8,167 meters, is in central Nepal. Its name means â€œWhite Mountainâ€ in Sanskrit, reflecting its snow-covered peaks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Although surveyed in the 19th century, it was first successfully climbed on 13 May 1960 by a Swiss-Austrian-German team; Kurt Diemberger, Peter Diener, Ernst Forrer, and Albin Schelbert, assisted by Sherpas Nawang Dorje and Nima Dorje. Dhaulagiri remains a challenging peak due to steep slopes, avalanches, and unpredictable weather.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of May 2025, a total of 680 climbers have successfully summited Dhaulagiri, the worldâ€™s seventh-highest peak, since its first ascent in 1960. This includes 42 climbers who reached the summit in 2024 and early 2025â€”29 in 2024 and 13 in 2025. By the end of 2023, 638 climbers had already reached the top, bringing the overall total to 680</p>', '1757310837.jpg', 7, 'MtDhaulagiri-I-', '1756975933718', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 18:37:13', '2025-09-08 15:38:57'),
(115, 171, 'MT. Manaslu', '(8th) Elev. 8,163 m |Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Manaslu (8,163 m) is the eighth-highest mountain in the world, located in Nepal. Its name derives from the Sanskrit word â€œManasaâ€, meaning spirit or soul, earning it the nickname â€œMountain of the Spirit.â€ The first successful ascent was on 9 May 1956 by a Japanese team including Toshio Imanishi and Sherpa Gyalzen Norbu. Known for its long ridges, glaciated terrain, and challenging weather, Manaslu is a demanding climb attracting mountaineers worldwide. Most expeditions occur in autumn, with some in spring and winter.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">By the end of 2023, 3,317 climbers had reached the summit (including foresummit), and 843 climbed without bottled oxygen. Seasonal totals: autumn 2,983, spring 312, winter 22, making autumn the most favored. Manaslu offers a challenging and adventurous experience for both experienced climbers and beginners.</p>', '1757310945.jpg', 8, 'MT-Manaslu', '1756976591746', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 18:48:11', '2025-09-08 15:40:45'),
(116, 171, 'MT. Nanga Parbat', '(9th) Elev. 8,126 m |Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nanga Parbat, the ninth-highest mountain in the world at 8,126 meters, is located in Pakistan. Its name means â€œNaked Mountainâ€ in Persian, reflecting its steep, exposed slopes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was made on 3 July 1953 by Hermann Buhl. The mountain is notorious for its extreme difficulty, massive vertical relief, and avalanche-prone terrain, earning it the nickname â€œKiller Mountainâ€. Approximately 400 mountaineers have successfully summited Nanga Parbat to date, with climbing becoming more frequent over the years, though it remains a highly challenging and dangerous peak. In July 2023, reports recorded over 60 summits in that month alone. By 2023, approximately 400 individual mountaineers had successfully summited Nanga Parbat. Successful ascents are rare, and the total number of attempts far exceeds the number of successful summits. The mountain has a history of high fatalities, with a mortality rate that fluctuated from 77% before 1990 to between 20.7% and 22%. Â </p>', '1757311869.jpg', 9, 'MT-Manaslu', '1756976592573', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 18:48:12', '2025-09-08 15:56:09'),
(117, 171, 'MT. Annapurna I', '(10th) Elev. 8,091 m| Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Annapurna I, the tenth-highest mountain in the world at 8,091 meters, is located in Nepal. Its name comes from Sanskrit, meaning â€œGoddess of Harvestsâ€, symbolizing abundance and nourishment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The mountain was first successfully climbed on 3 June 1950 by a French expedition led by Maurice Herzog and Louis Lachenal. Annapurna I is known for its steep faces, avalanche-prone slopes, and technical difficulty, making it one of the most challenging of the 8,000-meter peaks. Despite its dangers, it has a long history of mountaineering and remains a coveted summit for climbers worldwide.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of early April 2025, 514 climbers have successfully summited Annapurna I, including 310 expedition members and 204 Sherpas, according to Alan Arnette citing the Himalayan Database. Annapurna I is known for being a particularly dangerous and challenging peak, with a lower success rate and higher fatality rate compared to Mount Everest, making each successful ascent a remarkable achievement of skill and perseverance.</p>', '1757311338.jpg', 10, 'MT-Annapurna-I', '1756977593960', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:04:53', '2025-09-08 15:47:18'),
(118, 171, 'MT. Gasherbrum I', '(11th) Elev. 8,080 m|Pakistan - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gasherbrum I, the eleventh-highest mountain in the world at 8,080 meters, is located on the border of Pakistan and China in the Karakoram range. It is also called â€œHidden Peakâ€ because of its remote location.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The mountain was first successfully climbed on 5 July 1958 by an American expedition, with climbers Pete Schoening and Andy Kauffman reaching the summit. Gasherbrum I is known for its technical difficulty, harsh weather, and remote access, making it a challenging peak even for experienced mountaineers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The collection of data for every successful summit on such remote peaks is not always meticulously kept or easily accessible, making a precise count difficult to ascertain. it is estimated to be less than 200, reflecting its challenging nature. For example, there were 17 successful ascents during the summer of 2025 alone, according to mountaineer Alan Arnette.</p>', '1757311569.jpeg', 11, 'MT-Gasherbrum-I-', '1756977750614', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:07:30', '2025-09-08 15:51:09'),
(119, 171, 'MT. Broad Peak', '(12th) Elev. 8,051 m | Pakistan - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Broad Peak, the twelfth-highest mountain in the world at 8,051 meters, is located on the border of Pakistan and China in the Karakoram range. It is also known as Falchan Kangri.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was made on 9 June 1957 by an Austrian expedition, with climbers Fritz Wintersteller, Marcus Schmuck, Kurt Diemberger, and Hermann Buhl reaching the summit. Broad Peak is known for its long summit ridge, technical challenges, and harsh weather, making it a demanding climb for mountaineers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of early April 2025, approximately 404 climbers have successfully summited Broad Peak (8,051 m), including its sub-peaks.Â </p>', '1757311960.jpg', 12, 'MT-Broad-Peak-', '1756978422516', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:18:42', '2025-09-08 15:57:40'),
(120, 171, 'MT. Gasherbrum II', '(13th) Elev. 8,034 m|Pakistan - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gasherbrum II (8,034 m), the thirteenth-highest mountain in the world, is located on the border of Pakistan and China in the Karakoram range. Also called K4, it was first successfully climbed on 7 July 1956 by an Austrian team: Fritz Moravec, Josef Larch, and Hans Willenpart.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Considered one of the easier 8,000-meter peaks technically, Gasherbrum II has seen many commercial expeditions, with hundreds of climbers reaching the summit over the years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The total number of successful ascents of Gasherbrum II is not precisely known, but it is estimated to be several hundred since the first ascent in 1956. Hundreds of climbers attempt the peak each year. In July 2023, several expeditions reported 30â€“40 climbers reaching the summit on different days, with at least 6â€“16 foreign climbers summiting on single days..</p>', NULL, 13, 'MT-Gasherbrum-II-8034-m-PakistanChina-', '1756978597806', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:21:37', '2025-09-04 21:02:01'),
(121, 171, 'MT. Shishapangma', '(14th) Elev. 8,027 m |China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Shishapangma, the fourteenth-highest mountain in the world at 8,027 meters, is located entirely in Tibet, China. Its local name, GosainthÄn, means â€œPlace of the Gods.â€</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was on 2 May 1964 by a Chinese expedition led by XÇ” JÃ¬ng. Shishapangma is considered one of the more accessible 8,000-meter peaks due to its relatively gentle slopes, though it still poses significant challenges such as high altitude, crevasses, and unpredictable weather.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of early 2025, the exact total number of successful ascents of Shishapangma is not precisely known due to limited and inconsistent reporting. By 2003, there were about 201 successful ascents to the main summit, with 19 fatalities, and by 2012, this had increased to 302 ascents with 25 fatalities. In 2008, the central summit had been reached over 750 times, though only around 50 climbers continued to the main summit. These figures indicate a gradual increase in successful climbs over the years. However, due to highly restricted permits issued by Chinese and Tibetan authorities, obtaining comprehensive and up-to-date statistics remains difficult.</p>', NULL, 14, 'MT-Shishapangma-', '1756978960850', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:27:40', '2025-09-07 12:56:24'),
(123, 172, 'MT. Gyachung Kang', '(1st) Elev. 7,952 m | Nepal - Tibet', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gyachung Kang (7,952 m), also called Gyachung Khang, is the highest mountain below 8,000 meters and the 15th highest in the world. It lies in the Mahalangur Himal range on the Nepalâ€“Tibet border, between Mount Everest and Cho Oyu. Its name comes from Sherpa and Tibetan traditions, though its exact meaning is unclear. The first ascent was on April 10â€“11, 1964 by a Japanese team: Yukihiko Kato, Kiyoto Sakaizawa, Pasang Phutar, K. Machida, and K. Yasuhisa. The expedition suffered a tragedy when Akio Otaki fell at ~7,750 meters and died.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">InÂ 1986, a Frenchâ€“Nepali team led by Jean-Claude Marmier made the first ascent without supplemental oxygen via the South Face and Southwest Pillar. In 1988, a South Korean team summited via the Southwest Face and Southwest Ridge. Despite its height, Gyachung Kang has had few ascents due to remoteness and technical difficulty. The exact number of successful ascents is not publicly recorded, but ongoing attempts are confirmed by tour operators and expedition companies since 1964.</p>', '1758095806.jpeg', 1, 'MT-Gyachung-Kang-', '1756979675857', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:39:35', '2025-09-17 17:41:46'),
(125, 172, 'MT. Annapurna II', '(2nd) Elev. 7,937 m|Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Annapurna II (7,937 m) is the easternmost peak of the Annapurna range in Nepal and the second-highest in the Annapurna massif after Annapurna I. It is the 16th-highest mountain in the world. Its name comes from Sanskrit, meaning â€œGoddess of the Harvestsâ€ or â€œFull of Food,â€ symbolizing nourishment and abundance. The first ascent was on May 17, 1960, by a British/Indian/Nepali team led by J. O. M. Roberts, with Richard Grant, Chris Bonington, and Ang Nyima reaching the summit. Annapurna II is known for its steep faces and avalanche-prone slopes, making it a serious and challenging climb. It has been climbed less frequently than other peaks of similar height, with fewer than 20 successful ascents.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Most expeditions follow the northwest ridge, the original 1960 route, though alternative lines have been attempted. Its technical difficulty and relative obscurity keep it among the less-visited high Himalayan summits.</p>', '1758095908.jpg', 2, 'MT-Annapurna-II-', '1756980680802', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 19:56:20', '2025-09-17 17:43:28'),
(126, 172, 'MT. Gasherbrum IV', '(3rd) Elev. 7,925 m|Pakistan - China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gasherbrum IV (7,925 m), the 17th-highest mountain in the world, is in the Karakoram range on the Pakistanâ€“China border. Its Balti name means â€œbeautiful mountainâ€ and is often called the â€œShining Wallâ€ due to its dramatic 2,500-meter west face. The first ascent was on August 6, 1958, by Walter Bonatti and Carlo Mauri via the Northeast Ridge, establishing its mountaineering fame.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">InÂ 1985, Robert Schauer and Wojciech Kurtyka made the first West Face ascent in alpine style, a landmark Himalayan achievement. Despite being below 8,000 meters, Gasherbrum IV is extremely challenging due to steep ridges, complex ice and rock routes, and severe weather. It is rarely climbed and remains one of the most respected major peaks in the Karakoram.</p>', '1758096044.jpg', 3, 'MT-Gasherbrum-IV', '1756980975958', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:01:15', '2025-09-17 17:45:44'),
(129, 172, 'MT. Himalchuli', '(4rth) Elev. 7,893 m| Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Himalchuli (7,893 m) is the second-highest peak of the Manaslu Himal in Nepal and the 18th-highest mountain in the world. The name comes from â€œHimalâ€ (snow mountain) and â€œChuliâ€ (peak), meaning â€œSnow Peak.â€ It has three main summits: Himalchuli Main (7,893 m), Himalchuli West (7,540 m), and Himalchuli East (7,893 m).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first ascent was made on May 24, 1960, by a Japanese team led by Hisashi Tanabe, with climbers Hisashi Tanabe and Masahiro Harada reaching the summit via the southeast face. The mountain is considered very difficult because of steep slopes, technical ice and rock sections, and avalanche danger.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Although one of Nepalâ€™s highest peaks, Himalchuli has seen very few ascents since 1960 and remains one of the least-climbed major mountains in the Himalayas.</p>', NULL, 4, 'MT-Himalchuli-', '1756981369729', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:07:49', '2025-09-04 21:14:11'),
(130, 172, 'MT. Distaghil Sar', '(5th) Elev. 7,885 m|Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Distaghil Sar (7,885 m) is the highest peak of the Hispar Muztagh subrange in the Karakoram, located in Pakistan. The name comes from local Wakhi or Balti language, though its exact meaning is not clearly documented.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first ascent was made on July 9, 1960, by a Germanâ€“Austrian expedition led by GÃ¼nther StÃ¶ckl. The summit team included Helmut Heuberger, Rainer Goeschl, and Hans Maier. The climb was achieved via the south ridge, which remains the standard route.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Distaghil Sar is considered highly challenging due to steep faces, crevassed glaciers, and unpredictable weather. Despite its height, it is rarely climbed, with only a few successful expeditions since 1960.</p>', NULL, 5, 'MT-Distaghil-Sar-', '1756981483518', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:09:43', '2025-09-04 21:15:26'),
(131, 172, 'MT. Ngadi Chuli', '(6th) Elev. 7,871 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ngadi Chuli (7,871 m), also known as Peak 29, is part of the Himalaya in Nepal and the 20th-highest mountain in the world. Its name, Ngadi Chuli, comes from local Nepali and Tibetan languages, though the exact meaning is not well documented.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first and only confirmed ascent was made on May 1979 by a Japanese expedition led by Kenji Kobayashi, who reached the summit with Naoki Takahashi. The mountain is extremely remote and technically demanding, featuring steep ice and rock faces, unstable snow conditions, and high avalanche risk. Ngadi Chuli remains one of the least-climbed high Himalayan peaks, with very few attempts recorded, making it one of the most difficult mountains to summit in Nepal.</p>', NULL, 6, 'MT-Ngadi-Chuli-', '1756981625675', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:12:05', '2025-09-04 21:16:48'),
(132, 172, 'MT. Nuptse', '(7th) Elev. 7,861 m| Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nuptse (7,861 m) is a prominent peak in the Khumbu region of Nepal, located just southwest of Mount Everest. Its name, Nuptse, means West Peak in Tibetan, reflecting its position as part of the Everest massif.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first ascent was made on May 16, 1961, by a British expedition led by Joe Brown and George Band. Climbers Dennis Davis, Sherpa Tashi, and Sherpa Dorje were part of the team that reached the summit via the south ridge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nuptse is known for its steep, rugged slopes and technical climbing challenges, including exposed ridges and unstable ice faces. Although it is lower than its Everest neighbor, it remains a difficult and rarely climbed peak compared to other mountains in the region, with relatively few successful ascents.</p>', '1758096387.jpg', 7, 'MT-Nuptse-', '1756982057579', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:19:17', '2025-09-17 17:51:27');
