(133, 172, 'MT. Khunyang Chhish', '(8th) Elev.7,823 m|Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Khunyang Chhish (7,823 m), also spelled Kunyang Chhish, is a major peak in the Hispar Muztagh subrange of the Karakoram mountains in Pakistan. Locally, it is known as â€œCorner Peakâ€, reflecting its prominent position in the region.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was made in 1971 by a Polish expedition led by Andrzej Zawada, who reached the summit via the south ridge, which remains the standard route. The peak is extremely challenging due to its steep slopes, technical ice and rock sections, unpredictable weather, and remote location, which requires complex logistics and long approaches. Khunyang Chhish has been successfully summited only a handful of times, making it one of the least-climbed major mountains in the Karakoram. Its East Summit (7,400 m) was first climbed in 2013 by HansjÃ¶rg Auer, Matthias Auer, and Simon Anthamatten, but the main summit remains a formidable and rarely attempted challenge.</p>', NULL, 8, 'MT-Khunyang-Chhish-', '1756982190844', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:21:30', '2025-09-04 21:19:11'),
(134, 172, 'MT. Masherbrum (K1)', '(9th) Elev.7,821 m|Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Masherbrum (K1) (7,821 m) is a prominent peak in the Karakoram range of Pakistan. The name Masherbrum comes from the Balti language, meaning â€œMather Mountainâ€. It was the first peak surveyed in the Karakoram during the British 1856 survey, initially labeled as K1. The first successful ascent was on July 14, 1955, by a Britishâ€“Pakistani expedition led by George Band, who reached the summit with Tony Streather. Masherbrum is known for its steep and technically demanding slopes, including mixed ice and rock routes. Despite its height being slightly lower than some neighboring peaks like K2, it remains a challenging climb and is much less frequented, offering a remote and personal mountaineering experience.</p>', NULL, 9, 'MT-Masherbrum-K1', '1756982343762', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:24:03', '2025-09-04 21:20:30'),
(135, 172, 'MT. Nanda Devi', '(10th) Elev. 7,816 m | India', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nanda Devi (7,816 m) is Indiaâ€™s second-highest mountain, located in the Garhwal Himalayas of Uttarakhand. Its name, meaning â€œBliss-Giving Goddessâ€ in Sanskrit, reflects the mountainâ€™s spiritual and cultural significance. The first successful ascent was made on August 29, 1936, by a Britishâ€“Indian expedition led by Noel Odell, with climbers navigating steep ridges and avalanche-prone slopes. Today, Nanda Devi is largely protected within the Nanda Devi Sanctuary, and climbing is strictly regulated, making successful summits rare. Its sharp peaks, snow-covered faces, and technical challenges continue to make it one of the most respected and least-climbed high Himalayan mountains.</p>', NULL, 10, 'MT-Nanda-Devi-', '1756982519590', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:26:59', '2025-09-04 21:22:35'),
(136, 172, 'MT. Kamet', '(11th) Elev. 7,756 m | India', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mount Kamet (7,756 m) is the third-highest mountain in India and part of the Garhwal Himalayas in Uttarakhand, near the border with Tibet (China). It was first climbed in 1931 by Frank Smythe, along with a British expedition team. Kamet is known for its imposing height, steep ridges, and glaciers, making it a challenging climb despite being lower than the 8,000-meter peaks. The mountain is surrounded by important trekking routes and high-altitude passes, such as the Nanda Devi Sanctuary region. Its relatively remote location and technical terrain mean that ascents are less frequent compared to more popular Himalayan peaks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The local name of Mount Kamet is typically just â€œKametâ€, which comes from the Tibetan word â€œKang Meniâ€, meaning something like â€œMountain of the Godâ€ or â€œDivine Mountain.â€ It is recognized by local Garhwali and Tibetan communities with reverence, reflecting both its spiritual significance and its towering presence in the Garhwal Himalayas.</p>', NULL, 11, 'MT-Kamet', '1756983320640', 1, 0, '2025-09-04 20:40:20', '2025-09-07 13:00:19'),
(137, 172, 'MT. Mount Gongga', '(12th) Elev. 7,556 m | China - Sichuan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mount Gongga (7,556 m), also known as Minya Konka, is the highest peak in Sichuan Province, China, located in the Daxue Shan range on the eastern edge of the Tibetan Plateau. Its Tibetan name, Mi\'nyÃ¢g Gong\'ga Riwo, translates to â€œWhite Ice Mountain of Minyangâ€, reflecting both its striking appearance and cultural significance.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was made on October 28, 1932, by American climbers Terris Moore and Richard Burdsall via the northwest ridge. Mount Gongga is renowned for its steep slopes, technical terrain, and unpredictable weather, making it one of the most challenging 7,000-meter peaks in the world. Its climbing history includes several tragic expeditions, and the total number of successful summits remains relatively low, highlighting the mountainâ€™s formidable difficulty and remote location.</p>', NULL, 12, 'MT-Mount-Gongga', '1756983537811', 1, NULL, '2025-09-04 20:43:57', '2025-09-04 20:43:57'),
(138, 172, 'MT. Changtse', '(13th) Elev. 7,543 m | Tibet, near Everest', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Changtse (7,543 m) is a major peak in Tibet, just north of Mount Everest. Its name means â€œNorth Peakâ€ in Tibetan. The first official ascent was on October 14, 1982, by a German expedition via the northeast ridge. Since then, a few international teams have reached the summit, including a Chinese-Japanese team in 1986, which included the first woman to climb Changtse.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The mountain is technically challenging with steep slopes and unpredictable weather, and it remainsÂ one of the less-climbed 7,000-meter peaks in the region, offering a remote alternative to nearby Everest.</p>', NULL, 13, 'MT-Changtse-', '1757043103818', 1, 0, '2025-09-05 13:16:43', '2025-09-05 13:18:05'),
(139, 172, 'MT. Mount Kongur', '(14th) Elev. 7,649 m | China', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mount Kongur (7,649 m) is the highest peak of the Kongur Shan range in Xinjiang, China. Its name comes from the local Uyghur language, meaning â€œWhite Peakâ€, reflecting its snow-covered summit. The first successful ascent was made in July 1981 by a Chinese expedition led by Xu Jing, who reached the summit via the northwest ridge. Mount Kongur is technically demanding, with steep rock and ice faces, glaciated slopes, and unpredictable weather. Its remote location in western China and challenging terrain have limited the number of expeditions, making it one of the less-frequented 7,000-meter peaks in the world.</p>', NULL, 14, 'MT-Mount-Kongur', '1757043429874', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:22:09', '2025-09-05 13:22:09'),
(140, 172, 'MT. Trivor', '(15th) Elev. 7,577 m | Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mount Trivor, also known as Trivor Sar, is a 7,577-meter peak located in the Hispar Muztagh subrange of the Karakoram in Gilgit-Baltistan, Pakistan. The name â€œTrivorâ€ is widely used in English and Urdu sources, and while it is sometimes written as Trivor Sar, no distinct indigenous local name has been documented. The mountain was first successfully climbed on August 17, 1960, by Wilfrid Noyce of the United Kingdom and Jack Sadler of the United States via the northwest ridge. The only other confirmed ascent came much later, on August 30, 1991, when a Japanese team led by Toshifumi Onuki and Atsushi Endo reached the summit from the north side through the Momhil Glacier, joining the same northwest ridge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Records indicate that Trivor has been summited onlyÂ twice, making it one of the lesser-climbed high peaks of the Karakoram despite its prominence and beauty.</p>', NULL, 15, 'MT-Trivor-', '1757043548623', 1, 0, '2025-09-05 13:24:08', '2025-09-07 15:41:15'),
(141, 172, 'MT. Baintha Brakk', '(16th) Elev. 7,285 m | Pakistan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Baintha Brakk (7,285 m), popularly known as The Ogre, is a prominent peak in the Batura Muztagh subrange of the Karakoram in Pakistan. Its local name comes from Balti language traditions, though the meaning is not precisely documented. The first successful ascent was made on August 13, 1977, by a Britishâ€“New Zealand team led by Chris Bonington, with climbers Doug Scott and Joe Tasker reaching the summit.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Baintha Brakk is infamous for its extreme technical difficulty, featuring steep rock faces, ice towers, and unstable snow, making it one of the most challenging mountains in the Karakoram. Due to its remoteness and high risk, the peak has seen only a handful of successful ascents, and it remains one of the least-climbed 7,000-meter peaks in the world.</p>', NULL, 16, 'MT-Baintha-Brakk-', '1757043728653', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:27:08', '2025-09-05 13:27:08'),
(142, 172, 'MT. Jitchu Drake', '(17th) Elev. 7,326 m | Bhutan', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Jitchu Drake (7,326 m) is a prominent peak located on the Bhutanâ€“Tibet border. Its name comes from Tibetan, often interpreted as â€œThe Horse of the Deityâ€, reflecting the mountainâ€™s religious significance in Bhutanese culture. The first recorded ascent was made in 1983 by a Japanese expedition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Jitchu Drake is technically demanding, featuring steep ice and rock faces, and access is limited due to both its remote location and Bhutanâ€™s restrictions on climbing sacred peaks. As a result, it has seen very few successful ascents, making it one of the most challenging and rarely attempted 7,000-meter mountains in the Himalayas.</p>', NULL, 17, 'MT-Jitchu-Drake-', '1757043854532', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:29:14', '2025-09-05 13:29:14'),
(143, 172, 'MT. Chomo Lhari', '(18th) Elev. 7,326 m | Bhutan - Tibet', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Chomo Lhari (7,326 m), also known as Jomolhari, is a major mountain on the Bhutanâ€“Tibet border. Its name means â€œMountain of the Goddessâ€ in Tibetan, reflecting its spiritual significance in both regions. The first ascent was achieved on May 6, 1937, by a British expedition led by Freddie Spencer Chapman.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Chomo Lhari is highly technical, featuring steep ice and rock faces, and access is challenging due to its remote location. Climbing is further restricted in Bhutan because of the mountainâ€™s religious importance, making it one of the least-attempted peaks in the Himalayas while remaining a revered and iconic summit for mountaineers and local communities alike.</p>', NULL, 18, 'MT-Chomo-Lhari-', '1757043975686', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:31:15', '2025-09-05 13:31:15'),
(144, 172, 'MT. Langtang Lirung', '(19th) Elev. 7,227 m|Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Langtang Lirung (7,227 m) is the highest peak in the Langtang Himal subrange of the Nepalese Himalayas, located southwest of the eight-thousander Shishapangma and approximately 35 km north of Kathmandu. The mountain is also known locally as Nandanli.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent of Langtang Lirung occurred on October 24, 1978, when Japanese climbers Seishi Wada and Pemba Tsering Sherpa reached the summit via the East Ridge. Since then, the peak has been climbed via various routes, including the southeast and north ridges.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Climbing Langtang Lirung is considered highly challenging due to its steep slopes, technical terrain, and unpredictable weather. As of the latest available data, 51 expeditions have attempted the summit, with 14 successful ascents and 16 fatalities. The most recent successful ascent was in October 2024, when Czech mountaineer Marek Holecek and Slovakian climber Ondrej Huserka achieved the first ascent of the mountain\'s formidable East Face.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Langtang Lirung remains one of Nepal\'s most technically demanding and least-climbed peaks, attracting experienced mountaineers seeking a challenging and remote adventure.</p>', NULL, 19, 'MT-Langtang-Lirung-', '1757044093569', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:33:13', '2025-09-05 13:33:13'),
(145, 172, 'MT. Pumori', '(20th) Elev. 7,161 m  ( Nepal/Tibet)', NULL, NULL, '1758096740.JPG', 29, 'MT-Pumori-', '1757044165645', 0, 0, '2025-09-05 13:34:25', '2025-09-17 17:57:20'),
(146, 172, 'MT. Pumori', '(20th) Elev. 7,161 m | Nepal - Tibet', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Pumori (7,161 m) is a prominent peak on the Nepalâ€“Tibet border, located just eight kilometers west of Mount Everest. Its name means â€œEverest Daughterâ€ in Sherpa, reflecting its close proximity to the worldâ€™s highest mountain. The first successful ascent was made on May 17, 1962, by a Germanâ€“Nepali expedition led by Gerhard Lenser. Pumori is a technically challenging mountain, featuring steep snow and ice slopes, exposed ridges, and unpredictable weather.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While it is popular among experienced climbers seeking a high-altitude training peak near Everest, the summit has seen relatively few ascents compared to more frequented mountains, maintaining its reputation as a demanding and less-crowded 7,000-meter peak.</p>', NULL, 20, 'MT-Pumori-', '1757044289618', 1, NULL, '2025-09-05 13:36:29', '2025-09-05 13:36:29'),
(147, 220, 'MT. Machapuchare', '(1st) Elev . 6,993 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Machapuchare (6,993 m), locally known as <strong data-start=\"35\" data-end=\"52\">Machhapuchhre</strong>, is a sacred mountain in Nepalâ€™s Annapurna Himal range. Its name means <strong data-start=\"124\" data-end=\"139\">â€œFish Tailâ€</strong> in Nepali, reflecting the twin summit ridges that resemble a fishâ€™s tail when viewed from a distance. Revered as the home of Lord Shiva, it has never been officially climbed. In 1957, a British team reached within 50 meters of the summit but turned back to honor local beliefs and a promise to King Mahendra.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Since then, Nepal has banned climbing permits, keeping the mountain untouched. Although there are unverified claims of an illegal ascent in the 1980s, Machapuchare remains officially unclimbed.</p>', '1758096804.jpg', 1, 'list-of-Mountains-', '1757080663568', 1, 0, '2025-09-05 23:42:43', '2025-09-17 17:58:24'),
(148, 220, 'MT. Num Ri', '(2nd) Elev. Ri  6,959 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Num Ri (6,959 m) is a striking mountain in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, part of the Mahalangur Himal. The name comes from Tibetan, where â€œNumâ€ means sky or radiance and â€œRiâ€ means mountain, giving it the meaning â€œSky Mountainâ€ or â€œRadiant Mountain.â€ The peak forms a long crest ending in a pyramid-shaped summit capped by hanging glaciers, and it stands near Island Peak, Cho Polu, and Baruntse.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Num Ri was first and only successfully climbed on November 7, 2002, by German climbers Olaf Rieck, Lydia Schubert, and Carsten Schmidt via the northwest ridge. Their ascent required two high camps and nearly 800 meters of fixed rope, with constant dangers from avalanches, falling ice, and collapsing glacier slabsâ€”one of which narrowly missed a climber at around 5,900 m. Despite the risks, the team safely reached the summit, making Num Ri one of the lesser-known but formidable peaks of the Khumbu Himal.</p>', NULL, 2, 'MT-Num-Ri', '1757314295555', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 16:36:35', '2025-09-08 16:54:25'),
(149, 220, 'MT. Kanjiroba', '(3rd) Elev. 6,883 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kanjiroba (6,883 m), locally known as à¤•à¤¾à¤à¥à¤œà¤¿à¤°à¥‹à¤¬à¤¾ (Kanjiroba), is a major peak in the Kanjiroba Himal of Nepalâ€™s Dolpa District, Karnali Province. The name comes from the local Tibetan and Nepali languages: â€œKanjiâ€ refers to the area or valley where the mountain is located, and â€œRobaâ€ means mountain, so the name roughly translates to â€œMountain of the Kanji area.â€ Rising to 6,883 meters with a prominence of 1,870 meters, it is one of the highest mountains in the region.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first successful ascent was made in 1970 by the Osaka City University Himalayan Expedition, which also explored the surrounding Patrasi Himal for the first time. Since then, Kanjiroba has been summited, though it remains less frequently climbed due to its remote location and challenging access.</p>', NULL, 3, 'MT-Kanjiroba-6883-m-22579-ft-Nepal', '1757314667681', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 16:42:47', '2025-09-08 16:56:56'),
(150, 220, 'MT. Ama Dablam', '(4rth) Elev. 6,812 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"90\" data-end=\"1072\">Ama Dablam (6,812 m) is a striking peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, located within Sagarmatha National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Its name comes from the Sherpa language: â€œAmaâ€ means mother, and â€œDablamâ€ refers to a traditional double-pendant containing pictures of the gods worn by Sherpa women. The mountainâ€™s long ridges are seen as the arms of a mother protecting her child, while the hanging glacier represents the dablam, symbolizing a motherâ€™s necklace. Ama Dablam was first successfully climbed on March 13, 1961, by Mike Gill (New Zealand), Barry Bishop (USA), Mike Ward (UK), and Wally Romanes (New Zealand) via the Southwest Ridge, which remains the most popular route. Known for its technical difficulty, the mountain requires advanced rock, snow, and ice climbing skills.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"90\" data-end=\"1072\">Â As of early 2025, over 6,000 successful summits have been recorded, with a summit success rate ranging between 60% and 75%, depending on weather and season.</p>', '1758096981.png', 4, 'MT-Ama-Dablam-6812-m-22349-ft-Nepal', '1757314883850', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 16:46:23', '2025-09-17 18:01:21'),
(152, 220, 'MT. Cho Polu', '(5th) Elev. 6,735 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cho Polu (6,735 m )Â is a prominent mountain located in the Mahalangur Range of eastern Nepal, situated between the popular trekking peak Imja Tse (Island Peak) and the more challenging Baruntse. The name Cho Polu is derived from the local Sherpa language, where \"Cho\" means \"lake\" and \"Polu\" means \"peak\", collectively translating to \"Lake Peak\". This name reflects the mountain\'s proximity to the glacial lakes in the region, particularly the Imja Tsho lake located to the west.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This mountainÂ is a remote and technically challenging peak in eastern Nepal. The first known ascent was a solo climb by Spanish climber Nil Bohigas Martorell on November 1, 1984, via the north face and northeast ridge, done without official permits. Earlier claims from 1954 (Norman Hardie) and 1964 (Japanese expedition) are disputed. The first official ascent was completed by a German teamâ€”Olaf Rieck, Dieter RÃ¼lker, Markus Walter, and GÃ¼nter Jungâ€”on November 12, 1999. Due to its difficult terrain and remote location, Cho Polu has had only a few recorded ascents.</p>', NULL, 5, 'MT-Cho-Polu-', '1757315279886', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 16:52:59', '2025-09-08 17:12:24'),
(153, 220, 'MT. Khumbutse', '(6th) Elev. 6,636 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"47\" data-end=\"394\">Khumbutse (6,636 m) is a prominent mountain located on the border between Nepal and China (Tibet). Its name derives from the Khumbu region in Nepal, indicating its position at the head of the Khumbu Valley, down which the Khumbu Glacier flows. The name \"Khumbutse\" reflects its geographical location and significance in the region.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"396\" data-end=\"795\">The first known ascent of Khumbutse was made in 1979 by Slovenian climber FranÄek Knez, who reportedly soloed the peak via its north face. This ascent is considered the first confirmed summit of the mountain. While there were earlier claims of ascents in 1954 by Norman Hardie and in 1964 by a Japanese expedition, these claims are disputed and not widely accepted in the climbing community.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"797\" data-end=\"1121\">Khumbutse remains a relatively less-climbed peak, with only a few recorded ascents. Its challenging terrain and technical routes contribute to its low summit frequency. The mountain\'s remote location and the necessity for advanced mountaineering skills further limit the number of expeditions attempting to reach its summit.</p>', NULL, 6, 'MT-Khumbutse-', '1757315814930', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:01:54', '2025-09-08 17:14:40'),
(154, 220, 'MT. Thamserku', '(7th) Elev.  6,623 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Thamserku (6,623 m), located in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region east of Namche Bazaar, is a prominent snow-covered peak. Thamserku, is believed to meanÂ <strong data-start=\"111\" data-end=\"143\">â€œThe Saddle of the Snow Godâ€</strong> in the Sherpa language. The mountain was given this name because of its graceful, saddle-shaped summit and sweeping ridgelines, which resemble a majestic saddle in the sky. The first ascent was made on November 4, 1964 by Lynn Crawford, Peter Farrell, John McKinnon, and Richard Stewart of Edmund Hillaryâ€™s Schoolhouse Expedition via the south ridge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In 2014, Russian climbers Alexander Gukov and Alexey Lonchinskiy completed the first ascent of the technically challenging southwest face. Thamserku remains relatively less climbed due to its remote location and difficult, technical routes.</p>', NULL, 7, 'MT-Thamserku-', '1757315997878', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:04:57', '2025-09-30 15:40:35'),
(155, 220, 'MT. Chulu East', '(8th) Elev. 6,584 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Chulu East (6,584 m) is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Annapurna region, part of the Damodar Himal range in Gandaki Province within the Annapurna Conservation Area. Its name Chulu means â€œthumbâ€ in the local language, likely referring to the mountainâ€™s distinctive shape. The first confirmed ascent was made in 1955 by a German expedition via the northeast ridge, which remains the standard climbing route.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The ascent involves glacier crossings, steep scree slopes, and sections requiring fixed ropes, making it a moderately technical climb. The summit success rate is approximatelyÂ 70â€“80%, depending on weather, acclimatization, and climbersâ€™ experience, with climbers rewarded by panoramic views of Annapurna II, III, IV, and Gangapurna.</p>', NULL, 8, 'MT-Chulu-East-', '1757316172686', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:07:52', '2025-09-08 17:09:58'),
(156, 220, 'MT. Taboche', '(9th) Elev. 6,495 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Taboche (6,495 m), also known as Tawoche, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, located near the villages of Pheriche and Dingboche. It is connected to Cholatse by a long ridge and lies across the Imja River from Ama Dablam. The first confirmed ascent was made on April 15, 1974, by a French expedition led by Yannick Seigneur, with team members Louis Dubost, Paul Gendre, and Jacques Brugirard.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â Notable subsequent ascents include the winter climb of the northeast face by Jeff Lowe and John Roskelley in 1989, and the first ascent of the north face by Japanese climbers Fumitaka Ichimura and Genki Narumi in 2009. Climbing Taboche requires technical skills, glacier travel, and steep slope navigation. The summit success rate is around 70â€“80%, depending on weather, acclimatization, and climbersâ€™ experience, offering panoramic views of the surrounding peaks including Ama Dablam.</p>', NULL, 9, 'MT-Taboche-6495-m-21310-ft-Nepal', '1757316878521', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:19:38', '2025-09-08 18:17:34'),
(157, 220, 'MT. Mera Peak', '(10th) Elev. 6,476 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mera Peak (6,476 m), located in Nepalâ€™s Mahalangur Himal within the Sagarmatha Zone, is the highest trekking peak in the country. Its name Mera comes from the local Sherpa language, meaning â€œmy,â€ reflecting its significance to the local community. The first confirmed ascent was made on May 20, 1953, by Colonel Jimmy Roberts and Sen Tenzing, a Sherpa who had assisted in the 1952 Everest expedition. Mera North, the highest of its three main summits, was first climbed in 1975 by French climbers Marcel Jolly, G. Baus, and L. Honills.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â The standard route involves glacier travel with sections requiring fixed ropes. Mera Peak is popular among trekkers and climbers, offering panoramic views of five of the worldâ€™s highest mountains: Everest, Lhotse, Makalu, Cho Oyu, and Kangchenjunga. The summit success rate is approximately 70â€“80%, depending on weather, acclimatization, and climbersâ€™ experience.</p>', NULL, 10, 'MT-Mera-Peak-6476-m', '1757317100778', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:23:20', '2025-09-08 17:23:20'),
(158, 220, 'MT. Hiunchuli', '(11th) Elev. 6,441 m |Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hiunchuli (6,441 m), locally known as Hiun Chuli, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Annapurna region near the entrance to the Annapurna Sanctuary. In the local Sherpa/Tamang language, Hiun refers to â€œsnowâ€ or â€œice,â€ and Chuli means â€œpeakâ€ or â€œsummit,â€ so the name roughly translates to â€œSnow Peak.â€ The first confirmed ascent was in October 1971 by Craig Anderson and his team via the southeast face.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The climb is challenging due to steep terrain, rockfalls, and avalanches, and the mountain is less frequently climbed because of its remote location and technical routes. The summit success rate is around 25%, reflecting the difficulty of the peak.</p>', NULL, 11, 'MT-Hiunchuli', '1757317304752', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:26:44', '2025-09-08 18:19:03'),
(159, 220, 'MT. Cholatse', '(12th) Elev. (6,440 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cholatse (6,440 m), locally known as Jobo Lhaptshan, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, located between the Gokyo and Khumbu valleys. Its name comes from Tibetan words: cho (lake), la (pass), and tse (peak), meaning â€œLake Pass Peak.â€Â </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first confirmed ascent was onÂ April 22, 1982, by an American team via the southwest ridge, while the north face was first climbed in 1996 by a French team. Cholatse is highly technical, involving steep rock and ice sections, and is considered a challenging alpine-style climb. Its summit success rate is relatively low due to the technical difficulty and demanding conditions.Its unique combination of aesthetics and technical difficulty sets it apart, and its summit success rate is relatively low due to these demanding conditions.</p>', NULL, 12, 'MT-Cholatse-6440-m-', '1757317535794', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:30:35', '2025-09-08 17:30:35'),
(160, 220, 'MT. Langshisa Ri', '(13th) Elev.  6,427 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Langshisa Ri (6,427 m), also called Langshisha Ri, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Jugal Himal range within Langtang National Park. Its name comes from Tibetan: â€œLangâ€ meaning â€œfollowingâ€ and â€œShisaâ€ meaning â€œyak,â€ translating to â€œFollowing Yaks Peak.â€ The first confirmed ascent was made on April 23, 1982, by Japanese climber Takuya Kajimoto and Sherpa Pasang Norbu. Originally considered a full expedition peak, it was later reclassified as a trekking peak by the Nepal Mountaineering Association in 2002, making it more accessible.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The climb is technically challenging, involving steep rock and ice sections, requiring advanced mountaineering skills. Langshisa Ri is unique for its panoramic views of surrounding giants such as Langtang Lirung, Ganchenpo, and Dorje Lakpa, offering both aesthetic beauty and a demanding climbing experience. The summit success rate is relatively low due to its technical difficulty and challenging terrain.</p>', NULL, 13, 'MT-Langshisa-Ri-', '1757317698768', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:33:18', '2025-09-08 17:33:18'),
(161, 220, 'MT. Kusum Kangguru', '(14th) Elev. 6,367 m |Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kusum Kangguru (6,367 m ), also known as Kusum Kangru, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region. Its name means â€œThree Snow Peaksâ€ in the local Sherpa language, referring to its distinctive triple summit. The mountain is highly technical, featuring steep rock and ice faces, multiple ridges, and a dramatic north face, making it one of the most challenging climbs in the region. The first ascent was achieved by New Zealand climber Bill Denz on October 7, 1981, via the southwest buttress, which also marked the first solo ascent and traverse. The second ascent, by a Japanese team, followed the southeast face five days later.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â Due to its technical difficulty and remote location, Kusum Kangguru has a low summit success rate of approximately 25â€“30%, attracting only experienced mountaineers seeking a demanding and rewarding climb.</p>', NULL, 14, 'MT-Kusum-Kangguru-', '1757317935952', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:37:15', '2025-09-08 17:38:34'),
(162, 220, 'MT. Island Peak', '(15th) Elev. (6,189 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"79\" data-end=\"979\">Island Peak (6,189 m), locally known as Imja Tse, is a popular trekking peak located in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region near the village of Chhukung. The name Imja Tse refers to its location above the Imja Glacier, while the nickname â€œIsland Peakâ€ was given by British climbers in 1953 because the peak rises like an island from the surrounding glaciers. The first ascent was made on May 6, 1953, by a British expedition including Tenzing Norgay, who later became famous for summiting Everest. Island Peak is considered a moderate climb suitable for trekkers with basic mountaineering experience, involving glacier travel, ice climbing, and the use of fixed ropes near the summit.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"79\" data-end=\"979\">Its popularity and relatively straightforward routes result in a high summit success rate, typically aroundÂ 70â€“80%, making it one of the most accessible peaks in the Himalayas for adventure climbers.</p>', NULL, 15, 'MT-Island-Peak-6189-m', '1757318162939', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:41:02', '2025-09-08 17:41:02'),
(163, 220, 'MT. 16.	Kongde Ri', '(16th) Elev. 6,187 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kongde Ri (6,187 m), also known as Kwangde Ri or Kwande, is a prominent peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, located about 4 km west of Namche Bazaar. The name Kongde means â€œHoly Peakâ€ in the Sherpa language, reflecting its spiritual significance to the local community. The first successful ascent was on October 17, 1975, by a Nepalese team led by Lhakpa Tenzing, Sonam Gyalzen, Shambhu Tamang, and Sonam Hisi via the south ridge. An earlier ascent of the East Peak was completed in 1973 by a German team. Kongde Ri is a multi-summit peak with steep rock and snow faces, making it technically challenging despite being classified as a trekking peak.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Its unique combination of dramatic terrain, panoramic views of Everest, Lhotse, Makalu, and Cho Oyu, and remote location makes it highly respected among climbers. The summit success rate is relatively low, around 20â€“30%, due to its technical difficulty and challenging conditions.</p>', NULL, 16, 'MT-16Kongde-Ri-', '1757318415808', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:45:15', '2025-09-08 17:45:15'),
(164, 220, 'MT. 17.	Lobuche East', '(17th) Elev. 6,119 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"69\" data-end=\"936\">Lobuche East (6,119 m) is a well-known trekking peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, situated near the village of Lobuche on the Everest Base Camp trail. Its name is derived from the nearby village, though the exact meaning in Sherpa is not clearly known. The peak was first successfully climbed on April 25, 1984, by Laurence Nielson along with Sherpa Ang Gyalzen via the East Ridge. Recognized as a trekking peak by the Nepal Mountaineering Association, Lobuche East features technical sections of snow and ice that require the use of crampons, ice axes, and fixed ropes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"69\" data-end=\"936\">The summit offers breathtaking panoramic views of Everest, Lhotse, Nuptse, and Pumori. With proper acclimatization and preparation, climbers achieve the summit in 70â€“90% of attempts, making it a popular choice for those seeking a challenging yet accessible Himalayan climb.</p>', NULL, 17, 'MT-17Lobuche-East-', '1757318562563', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:47:42', '2025-09-08 17:47:42'),
(165, 220, 'Mt. Nirekha Peak', '(18th) Elev. 6,069 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nirekha Peak (6,069 m) is a notable trekking peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, situated near the Gokyo Valley and Cho La Pass. Its local name, Nirekha, is linked to the peakâ€™s distinctive ridge formation, though the exact translation is unclear. The first successful ascent was made in the early 1980s via the south or southeast ridges. Classified as a moderate-to-technical trekking peak, Nirekha involves climbing snow and ice slopes, requiring crampons, ice axes, and basic rope techniques. From the summit, climbers can enjoy sweeping views of nearby giants such as Cho Oyu, Everest, and Ama Dablam.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The peak has a summit success rate of aboutÂ 60â€“75%, making it a popular choice for trekkers aiming to experience high-altitude Himalayan climbing with manageable technical challenges.</p>', NULL, 18, 'Mt-Nirekha-Peak-6069-m', '1757318719559', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:50:19', '2025-09-08 17:50:19'),
(166, 220, 'MT. Kwangde Peak', '(19th) Elev. 6,011 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kwangde Peak (6,011 m) is a trekking peak in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region, near Namche Bazaar. Its local Sherpa name, Kwangde, carries cultural significance, though its exact meaning is not clearly documented. The first successful ascent took place in the 1980s. Classified as a moderate-to-technical trekking peak, Kwangde features snow and ice slopes, ridges, and some exposed sections, requiring the use of crampons, ice axes, and basic rope skills.Â </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The summit provides stunning panoramic views of major Himalayan peaks such as Everest, Lhotse, and Ama Dablam. With a summit success rate of around 60â€“70%, it is a popular choice for trekkers looking to experience high-altitude climbing in the Himalayas without extreme technical challenges.</p>', NULL, 19, 'MT-Kwangde-Peak', '1757318925978', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 17:53:45', '2025-09-08 17:53:45'),
(167, 220, 'MT. Pisang Peak', '(20th) Elev. 6,091 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Pisang Peak (6,091 m) is a trekking peak in Nepalâ€™s Manang region, situated along the Annapurna Circuit. Its local name, Pisang, comes from the nearby village, though the exact meaning is not clearly documented. The first recorded ascent was in the mid-20th century. Pisang Peak is considered a moderate trekking peak, featuring snow and ice slopes with some exposed sections that require crampons, ice axes, and basic rope techniques.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The summit provides beautiful views of the Annapurna range, including Annapurna II, Gangapurna, and Pisang Peakâ€™s neighboring peaks. Its summit success rate is relatively high, around 70â€“85%, making it a popular peak for trekkers and climbers seeking their first high-altitude Himalayan experience.</p>', NULL, 20, 'MT-Pisang-Peak', '1757319079601', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 17:56:19', '2025-09-08 17:57:20'),
(168, 220, 'MT. Ramdung Go Peak', '(21st) Elev. 5,925 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"73\" data-end=\"814\">Ramdung Go Peak (5,925 m) is a trekking peak situated in Nepalâ€™s Khumbu region near Dingboche village. The name Ramdung Go comes from the local Sherpa language, though its precise meaning is not well-documented. The first successful ascent occurred in the late 20th century. As a moderate trekking peak, it features snow and ice slopes that require basic mountaineering skills, including the use of crampons, ice axes, and ropes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" data-start=\"73\" data-end=\"814\">Â From the summit, climbers are rewarded with spectacular views of surrounding Himalayan giants such as Ama Dablam, Lhotse, and Island Peak. With a relatively high summit success rate of 65â€“75%, Ramdung Go is a popular option for trekkers seeking their first high-altitude Himalayan climb.</p>', NULL, 21, 'MT-Ramdung-Go-Peak-', '1757319351977', 1, NULL, '2025-09-08 18:00:51', '2025-09-08 18:00:51'),
(169, 220, 'MT. 22.	Pokalde â€“ 5,806 m (19,049 ft) â€“ Nepal', '(22nd) Elev. 5,806 m ( Nepal', NULL, NULL, NULL, 30, 'MT-22Pokalde-5806-m-19049-ft-Nepal', '1757319416726', NULL, NULL, '2025-09-08 18:01:56', '2025-09-08 18:01:56'),
(170, 220, 'MT. Pokalde', '(22nd) Elev. 5,806 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p>Pokalde (5,806 m), is a notable peak in the Khumbu region of Nepal. Often classified as a trekking peak, it provides climbers with an accessible yet rewarding Himalayan climbing experience.Â Pokalde, locally known as <strong data-start=\"26\" data-end=\"42\">Pokalde Peak</strong> (sometimes called <strong data-start=\"61\" data-end=\"75\">Pokalde Ri</strong>), does not have a widely documented unique meaning in Nepali or Sherpa language like some other Himalayan peaks. However, in the local Sherpa dialect, \"Ri\" means \"mountain\" or \"peak,\" so the name essentially refers to <strong data-start=\"294\" data-end=\"314\">Pokalde Mountain</strong>. The origin of the word \"Pokalde\" itself is less clear but is traditionally used by local communities to identify this peak in the Khumbu region.<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>The ascent of Pokalde offers beautiful landscape views of surrounding mountains. The first recorded ascent of <strong data-start=\"29\" data-end=\"40\">Pokalde</strong> was in <strong data-start=\"48\" data-end=\"56\">1953</strong> by a <strong data-start=\"62\" data-end=\"83\">German expedition</strong>. This climb marked Pokalde as a notable trekking peak in the Khumbu region, attracting mountaineers seeking experience before attempting higher Himalayan peaks.Its snow-covered slopes and relatively moderate climbing routes make it both challenging and achievable for climbers with some prior experience.</p>', NULL, 22, 'MT-Pokalde-', '1757319809610', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 18:08:29', '2025-09-08 18:27:25'),
(171, 220, 'MT. Yala Peak', '(23rd) Elev. 5,520 m | Nepal', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Yala Peak (5,520 m) is a trekking peak located in Nepalâ€™s Langtang region, near the village of Yala. Its local name, Yala, comes from the nearby area, though the exact meaning in the Sherpa language is not clearly documented. The peak was first climbed in the late 20th century. The summit provides best views of Langtang Lirung, Ganesh Himal and surrounding peaks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Yala PeakÂ in Nepalâ€™s Langtang region is a popular trekking peak suitable for climbers with basic mountaineering skills. The climb involves snow and moderate ice slopes, using crampons and ice axes. Since the first ascent in the late 20th century, around 1,200â€“1,500 climbers have reached the summit. The peak has a high success rate of 75â€“85%, making it an accessible and frequently climbed Himalayan peak.</p>', NULL, 23, 'MT-Yala-Peak-', '1757320268570', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 18:16:08', '2025-09-08 18:27:52'),
(172, 173, 'Carole Desmaris', 'Grand Voyageuse. Alsace France', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">\"J\'ai connu Mingmar en 2012 lors d\'un trek au Langtang. Mon premier sÃ©jour au NÃ©pal via l\'agence Allibert. Celui qui m\'a le plus marquÃ© et qui m\'a donnÃ© envie de revenir. GrÃ¢ce Ã  Mingmar. Il Ã©tait aux petits soins pour nous, trÃ¨s Ã  l\'Ã©coute, toujours souriant, disponible, nous parlant de son pays avec passion et se pliant en quatre pour que notre sÃ©jour soit inoubliable. Et il l\'a Ã©tÃ©. En tout point ! Autant sur le plan sportif que sur le plan humain ! Une vraie leÃ§on de vie.Â </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">Un tÃ©moignage aussi sur sa capacitÃ© Ã  rÃ©agir et Ã  gÃ©rer les imprÃ©vus, que ce soit quand notre \"sirdar\" pour des raisons personnels a dÃ» nous quitter ou lorsqu\'un membre du groupe a eu le mal des montagnes. Dans les deux cas, la situation a Ã©tÃ© gÃ©rÃ©e avec brio.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">Nous sommes toujours restÃ©s en contact depuis cette rencontre et avons peu Ã  peu tissÃ© des liens d\'amitiÃ©.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">Partir avec Lhakpa Treeking, compte-tenu de l\'expÃ©rience passÃ©e de son fondateur, est la certitude de vivre un sÃ©jour inoubliable, de partager des moments uniques et de revenir avec des Ã©toiles dans les yeux. </span>En toute sÃ©curitÃ©. Je recommande !\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">ğŸ“§ cdesmaris@live.fr</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â </p>', NULL, 31, 'Carole-Desmaris', '1757330223507', 1, 0, '2025-09-08 21:02:03', '2025-09-30 13:17:40'),
(174, 232, 'Januka Shresthe', 'Australia', 'English French', '<p data-start=\"232\" data-end=\"545\">I am <strong data-start=\"237\" data-end=\"256\">Januka Shrestha</strong>, a professional <strong data-start=\"273\" data-end=\"319\">French and English-speaking trekking guide</strong>. Since <strong data-start=\"327\" data-end=\"335\">2010</strong>, I have had the pleasure of guiding travelers from around the world with great passion and dedication. Over the years, I have had the privilege of working with several <strong data-start=\"504\" data-end=\"542\">renowned European travel companies</strong>.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"547\" data-end=\"861\">Currently, I am based in <strong data-start=\"572\" data-end=\"585\">Australia</strong>, yet I remain proudly connected with <strong data-start=\"623\" data-end=\"652\">Lhakpa Trekking Pvt. Ltd.</strong>, a company deeply committed to both <strong data-start=\"689\" data-end=\"707\">safe adventure</strong> and <strong data-start=\"712\" data-end=\"733\">community welfare</strong>. Through <strong data-start=\"743\" data-end=\"765\">Nepal Care Concern</strong>, we focus on enhancing <strong data-start=\"789\" data-end=\"858\">educational opportunities for children in remote regions of Nepal</strong>.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"863\" data-end=\"968\">Please feel free to <strong data-start=\"883\" data-end=\"897\">contact us</strong> for a truly <strong data-start=\"910\" data-end=\"965\">memorable and meaningful travel experience in Nepal</strong>.</p>', '1759840580.jpg', 32, 'Januka-Shresthe', '1759840580867', 1, 0, '2025-10-07 22:21:20', '2025-12-15 18:59:06');
