trekking, peak tourist time</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Winter</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>December â€“ February</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Cold temperatures, snowfall at high altitudes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Suitable for lower-altitude treks, high passes may be closed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 1, '2024-09-02 14:29:34', '2025-08-20 12:56:24'),
(521, 122, 'Tips and Gratitude', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tipping is a long-standing tradition in the adventure sector in Nepal and a meaningful way to show appreciation for the hard work of guides, porters, and trekking staff. While not mandatory, it is customary to tip at the end of the trek, usually as a group, to ensure a fair and organised distribution. Your trek guide will advise on an appropriate amount based on the trek duration and team size. Many groups present tips with a small farewell gathering or celebration on the last evening, marking the end of their trek. Additionally, trekkers often choose to donate equipment such as boots, gloves, hats, scarves, and trekking poles to the porters and crew. These items are highly valued and appreciated, especially by those working in the mountains. Tour leaders can be tipped separately during the final group dinner in Kathmandu or Pokhara. Though not obligatory, a small personal token of gratitude for their efforts enhances the spirit of mutual respect and appreciation.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, '2024-09-02 14:29:34', '2025-08-20 12:56:24'),
(522, 122, 'Currency & Payments', '<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Accepted Currencies â€“ Nepali Rupees (NPR), US Dollars (USD), Euros (EUR), and British Pounds (GBP) are widely accepted.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">ATMs &amp; Card Payments â€“ Available in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara, but limited in trekking areas. Carry cash for mountain regions.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Higher Prices at Altitude â€“ Expect higher costs as supplies are carried up manually or by yaks.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, '2024-09-02 14:29:34', '2025-08-20 12:56:24'),
(523, 122, 'Personal Expenses', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Trekking in Nepal includes most major costs, but PERSONAL EXPENSES vary depending on individual spending habits. On average, â‚¬200 ($200-250 USD) should cover:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Beverages â€“ Soft drinks, tea, coffee, and alcoholic drinks (prices increase with altitude).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Snacks &amp; Extras â€“ Chocolates, energy bars, and personal food purchases along the trek.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Souvenirs â€“ Handicrafts, prayer flags, and traditional items from trekking villages.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tips for Guides &amp; Porters â€“ Tipping is customary in Nepal; recommended $5-$10 per day for guides and $3-$5 for porters.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, '2024-09-02 14:29:34', '2025-08-20 12:56:24'),
(524, 122, 'What\'s not included', '<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Travel Insurance</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">International flight</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tips for porters and other trek staff</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">Drinks, souvenirs, Wifi internet, etc.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Anything not listed under \" price includes</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, '2024-09-02 14:29:34', '2025-08-20 12:56:24'),
