(1273, 169, 'Best time to visit Nepal', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Frankly, Nepal is an all-season tourism destination. However, for adventure enthusiasts, there are 2 major seasons to visit Nepal. Here is a detailed look at the seasons and their weather patterns in Nepal for you to decide when best to visit:</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p><strong>Season</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p><strong>Months</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p><strong>Weather Characteristics</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p><strong>Trekking Conditions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Spring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>March â€“ May</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Mild temperatures, clear skies, blooming rhododendrons</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Excellent for trekking, colorful landscapes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Summer/ Monsoon</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>June â€“ August</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Heavy rainfall, humid, cloudy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Difficult due to slippery trails and poor visibility</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Autumn</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>September â€“ November</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Stable weather, clear skies, moderate temperatures</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Best season for trekking, peak tourist time</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Winter</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>December â€“ February</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Cold temperatures, snowfall at high altitudes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Suitable for lower-altitude treks, high passes may be closed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-09-03 12:45:29'),
(1274, 169, 'Weather condition in Nepal', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Spring season (March - May)Â </strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 30Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â <strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Stable weather, clear mornings, occasional afternoon clouds.</li>\r\n<li>Flowers and rhododendrons bloom, making the trails scenic.</li>\r\n<li>Increasing humidity in late May, signaling the approaching monsoon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â <strong>Best Treks for Spring:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp (EBC) Trek â€“ Best visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Annapurna Circuit â€“ Lush landscapes and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Langtang Valley Trek â€“ Ideal for nature lovers with vibrant forests.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Summer/Monsoon (June â€“ August)</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 20Â°C â€“ 35Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: 0Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Heavy rainfall (average 200â€“500mm per month), especially in July and August.</li>\r\n<li>Frequent landslides and flight cancellations, especially in hilly areas.</li>\r\n<li>Leeches on lower-altitude trails due to humidity.</li>\r\n<li>Best Treks for Summer: (Only in rain-shadow areas with minimal rainfall)</li>\r\n<li>Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from monsoon.</li>\r\n<li>Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Autumn (September â€“ November) â€“ Best Trekking Season</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 28Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Stable weather, crystal-clear skies, and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Best visibility of Himalayan peaks, making it the most popular season.</li>\r\n<li>Crowded trekking trails, especially on Everest Base Camp and Annapurna Circuit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Best Treks for Autumn:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp Trek â€“ Peak visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Manaslu Circuit Trek â€“ Challenging but scenic and less crowded.</li>\r\n<li>Gokyo Lakes Trek â€“ Stunning turquoise glacial lakes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Winter (December â€“ February)</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 2Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -15Â°C â€“ 10Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Cold temperatures, snowfall at higher elevations.</li>\r\n<li>Shorter daylight hours, some high passes (e.g., Thorong La) may be closed.</li>\r\n<li>Fewer trekkers, offering solitude.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Best Treks for Winter: (Lower-altitude treks to avoid extreme cold)</strong></p>\r\n<ul class=\"uk-includes uk-margin-top uk-margin-bottom\">\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ghorepani Poon Hill Trek â€“ Short, scenic trek with snow-capped views.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Everest Panorama Trek â€“ Lower-altitude trek with Everest views.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Helambu Trek â€“ Close to Kathmandu, no high passes.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-09-03 12:45:29'),
(1275, 169, 'Best Treks & Destination', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>In summer</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from the monsoon.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Best destination in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is tough to say because every destination in Nepal is a wonder on itself. Broadly, from adventure perspective, youâ€™ll find two major types of destinations. The first ones are the most popular ones which often are the most accessible and will have huge number of trekkers in seasons. These destinations often have a long history of exploration and something of global sensation what make them popular every year. These destinations include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Everest Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Sanctuary Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Dolpo Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Langtang Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Manaslu Circuit Trek, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Then, there are these other groups of destinations which are not as popular but offer an unmatched level of serenity, peace and wilderness that is hardly found anywhere. They offer the true sense of adventure, experience and the thrill of exploration. These destinations in Nepal include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Ruby Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tamang Heritage Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Api Himal Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">The Great Himalayan Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Makalu Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sherpini Col Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Kanchenjunga Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dhaulagiri Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sisne Himal Trek, and so on.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The choice of your destination depends on your time, cost, and the experience you wish to have.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-08-20 18:41:46'),
(1276, 169, 'Emergency Contacts  and safety', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you a mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travelers: Nepal is safe for solo travelers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>SIM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. Internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Emergency Numbers:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-08-20 18:41:46'),
(1280, 169, 'Food and Accommodation', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Food (meal plan) and accommodation are among the most important things when in Nepal and in course of the trek. Please make sure to let the booking agency know of your allergies if you have any and also let them know if you are in any personal medication and need special attention at any time during the trek.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Accommodation in Kathmandu and Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Hotel Standards â€“ Most trekkers stay in 2-3 star hotels in Thamel (Kathmandu) or Lakeside (Pokhara) before and after trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Twin-Sharing Basis â€“ Standard bookings are twin-sharing, but single rooms can be arranged at an extra cost.</li>\r\n<li>Facilities â€“ Hotels offer hot showers, Wi-Fi, laundry services, and 24-hour electricity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Accommodation in Trekking Regions</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Teahouses / Lodges â€“ These are family-run guesthouses with dorm-style or twin rooms.</li>\r\n<li>Basic Bedding â€“ Rooms have wooden beds, foam mattresses, blankets, and pillows, but heating is not available in most lodges.</li>\r\n<li>Shared Bathrooms â€“ Most lodges have shared toilets and limited hot water (solar-heated in some places).</li>\r\n<li>Dining Areas â€“ Warm communal dining halls serve as social hubs for trekkers.</li>\r\n<li>Electricity &amp; Wi-Fi â€“ Available in lower-altitude teahouses but may require extra charges at higher altitudes.</li>\r\n<li>No Single Rooms at Higher Altitudes â€“ In remote areas, multi-bedded rooms may be the only option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Meals in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast &amp; Dinner â€“ Served at hotels or local restaurants.</li>\r\n<li>Wide Food Selection â€“ Includes Nepali, Indian, Chinese, and Western cuisine.</li>\r\n<li>Popular Dishes â€“ Dal Bhat (lentils &amp; rice), Momos (dumplings), Thukpa (Tibetan noodle soup), pizza, pasta, curries, and grilled meats.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Meals During Trekking</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Standard Trekking Meal Plan â€“ Breakfast, lunch, and dinner included in most trekking packages.</li>\r\n<li>Dining at Lodges â€“ Meals are prepared in teahouse kitchens, with all trekkers typically eating the same menu.</li>\r\n<li>Ordering in Advance â€“ Due to limited supplies in remote areas, meals must be ordered in advance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Common Meals on Treks</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast: porridge, pancakes, Tibetan bread, chapati, eggs, tea/coffee.</li>\r\n<li>Lunch &amp; Dinner: Dal Bhat (lentil soup, rice, vegetables), noodles, pasta, potatoes, soups, and curries.</li>\r\n<li>Vegetarian Options Available: Meat is available at lower altitudes but not recommended at high altitudes due to storage concerns.</li>\r\n<li>Soup &amp; Hydration: Garlic soup is often recommended as it helps with acclimatization.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Water &amp; Hydration</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Drinking Water Safety â€“ Tap water is not safe for drinking in Nepal.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Filtered/Boiled Water Provided â€“ Teahouses offer boiled or filtered water (often at extra cost).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Water Purification Recommended â€“ Trekkers should bring purification tablets, LifeStraw, or Water-to-Go bottles.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Avoid Plastic Bottles â€“ Buying bottled water is expensive and environmentally harmful.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 10, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-10-16 18:39:19'),
(1281, 169, 'Altitude Sickness', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Altitude sickness, also known as Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS), occurs when the body fails to adapt to lower oxygen levels at high altitudes. It typically affects trekkers above 2,500 meters (8,200 ft) and can range from mild discomfort to life-threatening conditions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are different types of altitude sickness. AMS is the most common and is the first stage in getting altitude sickness. AMS if left unchecked goes on to become dangerous.</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p><strong>Type</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p><strong>Symptoms</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p><strong>Altitude Range</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p><strong>Severity</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Headache, nausea, dizziness, fatigue, loss of appetite, difficulty sleeping</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>2,500m â€“ 5,500m (8,200ft â€“ 18,000ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Mild to Moderate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Shortness of breath, persistent cough (frothy sputum), chest tightness, blue lips/nails</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 3,500m (11,500ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Severe &amp; Life-Threatening</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Cerebral Edema (HACE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Confusion, loss of coordination (ataxia), severe headache, unconsciousness</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 4,000m (13,100ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Fatal if Untreated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.25in; text-indent: -1.25in; text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">Note</span></strong><span style=\"mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\">: <strong>HAPE and HACE</strong> are medical emergencies that require immediate descent and oxygen treatment.</span></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 11, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-08-20 18:41:46'),
(1282, 169, 'Altitude Sickness Risks', '<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â Â Rapid Ascent â€“ Climbing too quickly without proper acclimatization.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Genetic Susceptibility â€“ Some individuals are naturally more prone.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Dehydration &amp; Overexertion â€“ Increases symptoms of AMS.Â </li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Previous History of AMS â€“ Higher risk if experienced before.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-10-16 18:39:19'),
(1283, 169, 'Prevention And Strategies', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>1. Follow the \"Golden Rule\" â€“ Climb High, Sleep Low</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Never ascend more than 500m (1,640ft) per day above 3,000m Or simply, follow your guide</li>\r\n<li>Every 1,000m (3,280ft) gain, take a rest/acclimatization day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>2. Stay Hydrated &amp; Maintain Nutrition</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Â Â Drink 3-4 liters of water daily to avoid dehydration.</li>\r\n<li>Â Â Eat carbohydrate-rich meals to sustain energy levels.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>3. Avoid Alcohol &amp; Sleeping Pills</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Alcohol dehydrates and worsens oxygen absorption.</li>\r\n<li>Sleeping pills suppress breathing and can increase AMS risk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>4. Use Acclimatization Stops</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Everest Base Camp Trek: Acclimatization at Namche Bazaar (3,440m) &amp; Dingboche (4,410m).Â Â Annapurna Circuit: Rest at Manang (3,540m) before crossing Thorong La Â </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>5. Medication (For High-Risk Trekkers)Â Â Â </strong>Â Â Â Â </p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Â Diamox (Acetazolamide) â€“ Helps prevent AMS; start 125-250mg twice daily before ascent.</li>\r\n<li>Â Dexamethasone â€“ Emergency treatment for severe altitude sickness.</li>\r\n<li>Â Nifedipine â€“ Used for HAPE cases.</li>\r\n<li>Â Please note that these medicines require a medical professionalâ€™s prescription and canâ€™t be consumed haphazardly.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>6. Descend Immediately if Symptoms Worsen</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If mild AMS symptoms persist, descend at least 300m (1,000ft).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If HAPE or HACE symptoms occur, descend immediately with medical help.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Emergency Treatment &amp; Evacuation in Nepal</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Supplemental Oxygen â€“ Available in some lodges and hospitals.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gamow Bag (Portable Altitude Chamber) â€“ Used in extreme cases.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Helicopter Evacuation â€“ Costs $5,000 â€“ $10,000 USD (covered by good insurance).</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 13, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-09-03 12:45:29'),
(1284, 169, 'Travel Advisory for Nepal', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Travel Advisory for Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Before travelling to Nepal, it\'s important to stay informed about safety, health and entry requirements. Below is a detailed travel advisory covering safety, health guidelines, political stability and essential travel tips.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Health &amp; Vaccinations</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Required Vaccines: No mandatory vaccines for entry, but the following are recommended:</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Hepatitis A &amp; B â€“ Due to potentially contaminated food or water.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Typhoid â€“ For protectionÂ against foodborne illnesses.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Rabies â€“ If planning extended stays in remote areas.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tetanus &amp; Diphtheria â€“ Basic precaution.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Malaria &amp; Dengue: Malaria risk is low in Nepalâ€™s trekking regions but present in southern Terai areas (Chitwan, Lumbini).</li>\r\n<li>Dengue outbreaks occur seasonally (especially during the monsoon). Use mosquito repellent and wear long sleeves in affected areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Political Stability &amp; Security</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>General Safety: Nepal is politically stable and safe for travellers.</li>\r\n<li>Border Security: Certain trekking areas (e.g., Upper Mustang, Manaslu) require special permits. Travel to remote border regions (Tibet, India) may be restricted without prior approval.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travellers: Nepal is safe for solo travellers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">IM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. The internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Emergency Numbers:</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 14, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-08-20 14:29:30'),
(1285, 169, 'About Nepal', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nestled between India and China, Nepal is a beautiful landlocked nation in South Asia. Nepal is renowned for having the highest mountain in the world, Mount Everest, and for its amazing Himalayan scenery, rich cultural legacy and friendly people. Lord Buddha was born there, and it\'s a popular destination for hikers, climbers and adventurers. A vibrant and spiritual destination, Nepal is remarkably diversified in terms of race, language and religion despite its tiny size.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Total Population of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of 2025, Nepal has a population of approximately 31.5 million people.<br>The population is diverse, with over 100 ethnic groups and languages.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Nepalis Working Abroad</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Roughly 15â€“20% of Nepalâ€™s population is working overseas, mostly in countries like India, Malaysia, Qatar, UAE, and Saudi Arabia.<br>Remittances from these workers make up about 20â€“25% of the national GDP, making it a major part of the economy.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Condition of Youth in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Many youths are unemployed or underemployed, even after getting a degree.<br>Due to limited job opportunities and political instability, a significant number choose to migrate abroad for work.<br>Despite challenges, Nepali youth are resilient, talented and active in fields like tech, tourism, and entrepreneurship.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Current Condition of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal is a developing country with immense natural beauty and potential, especially in tourism and hydropower.<br>Major challenges include poverty, unemployment, infrastructure issues, and a high dependency on foreign aid and remittance.<br>Thereâ€™s a growing urban-rural gap, and many remote areas still lack basic services. Â  Â  Â Â </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Political Situation</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal is a federal democratic republic, but its political landscape is often unstable and fragmented. Frequent changes in government, internal party conflicts and a lack of long-term vision have slowed national progress.<br>Citizens are hopeful for better leadership and accountability, especially from the younger generation of politicians.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 15, 1, '2025-07-26 16:03:13', '2025-08-21 16:03:48'),
(1287, 163, 'Best Treks & Destination', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in; text-align: justify;\"><strong>In summer</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from the monsoon.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in; text-indent: -13.5pt; text-align: justify;\"><strong>Best destination in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in; text-align: justify;\">This is tough to say because every destination in Nepal is a wonder on itself. Broadly, from adventure perspective, youâ€™ll find two major types of destinations. The first ones are the most popular ones which often are the most accessible and will have huge number of trekkers in seasons. These destinations often have a long history of exploration and something of global sensation what make them popular every year. These destinations include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Everest Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Sanctuary Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Dolpo Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Langtang Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Manaslu Circuit Trek, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in; text-align: justify;\">Then, there are these other groups of destinations which are not as popular but offer an unmatched level of serenity, peace and wilderness that is hardly found anywhere. They offer the true sense of adventure, experience and the thrill of exploration. These destinations in Nepal include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Ruby Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tamang Heritage Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Api Himal Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">The Great Himalayan Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Makalu Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sherpini Col Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Kanchenjunga Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dhaulagiri Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sisne Himal Trek, and so on.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in; text-align: justify;\">The choice of your destination depends on your time, cost, and the experience you wish to have.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 1, '2025-08-12 13:05:26', '2025-08-20 13:43:26'),
(1288, 163, 'Emergency Contacts & Safety', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Crime &amp; Personal Safety</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you a mental relief.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Solo Travelers: Nepal is safe for solo travelers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Transportation Safety</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square; text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">SIM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. Internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Emergency Numbers:</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Tourist Police: 1144</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">General Police: 100</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Ambulance: 102</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</span></li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 1, '2025-08-12 13:12:42', '2025-12-07 22:09:42'),
(1289, 147, 'WHAT\'S  INCLUDED', '<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ground travel as specified in the programme.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Domestic flights as described.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Accommodation as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hotel as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Meals as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Entrance fee to Annapurna Park.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Professional guide</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Assistance from a local team during the trek.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">A first aid kit.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">1 porter for 2 clients</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1290, 147, 'WHAT\'S NOT INCLUDED', '<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Travel Insurance</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">International flight</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tips for porters and other trek staff</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"FR\">Drinks, souvenirs, Wifi internet, etc.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Anything not listed under \" price includes\"</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-10-16 17:37:45'),
(1291, 147, 'PERSONAL EXPENSES', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Trekking in Nepal includes most major costs, but PERSONAL EXPENSES vary depending on individual spending habits. On average, â‚¬200 ($200-250 USD) should cover:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Beverages â€“ Soft drinks, tea, coffee, and alcoholic drinks (prices increase with altitude).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Snacks &amp; Extras â€“ Chocolates, energy bars, and personal food purchases along the trek.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Souvenirs â€“ Handicrafts, prayer flags, and traditional items from trekking villages.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tips for Guides &amp; Porters â€“ Tipping is customary in Nepal; recommended $5-$10 per day for guides and $3-$5 for porters.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1292, 147, 'CURRENCY & PAYMENT', '<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Accepted Currencies â€“ Nepali Rupees (NPR), US Dollars (USD), Euros (EUR), and British Pounds (GBP) are widely accepted.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">ATMs &amp; Card Payments â€“ Available in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara, but limited in trekking areas. Carry cash for mountain regions.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Higher Prices at Altitude â€“ Expect higher costs as supplies are carried up manually or by yaks.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1293, 147, 'TIPS & GRATITUDE', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tipping is a long-standing tradition in the adventure sector in Nepal and a meaningful way to show appreciation for the hard work of guides, porters, and trekking staff. While not mandatory, it is customary to tip at the end of the trek, usually as a group, to ensure a fair and organised distribution. Your trek guide will advise on an appropriate amount based on the trek duration and team size. Many groups present tips with a small farewell gathering or celebration on the last evening, marking the end of their trek. Additionally, trekkers often choose to donate equipment such as boots, gloves, hats, scarves, and trekking poles to the porters and crew. These items are highly valued and appreciated, especially by those working in the mountains. Tour leaders can be tipped separately during the final group dinner in Kathmandu or Pokhara. Though not obligatory, a small personal token of gratitude for their efforts enhances the spirit of mutual respect and appreciation.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1294, 147, 'BEST TIME TO VISIT NEPAL', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Frankly, Nepal is an all-season tourism destination. However, for adventure enthusiasts, there are 2 major seasons to visit Nepal. Here is a detailed look at the seasons and their weather patterns in Nepal for you to decide when best to visit:</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p><strong>Season</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p><strong>Months</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p><strong>Weather Characteristics</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p><strong>Trekking Conditions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Spring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>March â€“ May</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Mild temperatures, clear skies, blooming rhododendrons</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Excellent for trekking, colorful landscapes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Summer/ Monsoon</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>June â€“ August</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Heavy rainfall, humid, cloudy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Difficult due to slippery trails and poor visibility</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Autumn</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>September â€“ November</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Stable weather, clear skies, moderate temperatures</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Best season for trekking, peak tourist time</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Winter</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>December â€“ February</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Cold temperatures, snowfall at high altitudes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Suitable for lower-altitude treks, high passes may be closed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1295, 147, 'WEATHER CONDITION IN NEPAL', '<p><strong>Spring season (March - May)Â </strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 30Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â <strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stable weather, clear mornings, occasional afternoon clouds.</li>\r\n<li>Flowers and rhododendrons bloom, making the trails scenic.</li>\r\n<li>Increasing humidity in late May, signaling the approaching monsoon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â <strong>Best Treks for Spring:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp (EBC) Trek â€“ Best visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Annapurna Circuit â€“ Lush landscapes and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Langtang Valley Trek â€“ Ideal for nature lovers with vibrant forests.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Summer/Monsoon (June â€“ August)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 20Â°C â€“ 35Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: 0Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Heavy rainfall (average 200â€“500mm per month), especially in July and August.</li>\r\n<li>Frequent landslides and flight cancellations, especially in hilly areas.</li>\r\n<li>Leeches on lower-altitude trails due to humidity.</li>\r\n<li>Best Treks for Summer: (Only in rain-shadow areas with minimal rainfall)</li>\r\n<li>Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from monsoon.</li>\r\n<li>Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Autumn (September â€“ November) â€“ Best Trekking Season</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 28Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stable weather, crystal-clear skies, and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Best visibility of Himalayan peaks, making it the most popular season.</li>\r\n<li>Crowded trekking trails, especially on Everest Base Camp and Annapurna Circuit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Best Treks for Autumn:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp Trek â€“ Peak visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Manaslu Circuit Trek â€“ Challenging but scenic and less crowded.</li>\r\n<li>Gokyo Lakes Trek â€“ Stunning turquoise glacial lakes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Winter (December â€“ February)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 2Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -15Â°C â€“ 10Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cold temperatures, snowfall at higher elevations.</li>\r\n<li>Shorter daylight hours, some high passes (e.g., Thorong La) may be closed.</li>\r\n<li>Fewer trekkers, offering solitude.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Best Treks for Winter: (Lower-altitude treks to avoid extreme cold)</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ghorepani Poon Hill Trek â€“ Short, scenic trek with snow-capped views.</li>\r\n<li>Everest Panorama Trek â€“ Lower-altitude trek with Everest views.</li>\r\n<li>Helambu Trek â€“ Close to Kathmandu, no high passes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-20 18:46:14'),
(1296, 147, 'Best Treks & Destination', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>In summer</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from the monsoon.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Best destination in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is tough to say because every destination in Nepal is a wonder on itself. Broadly, from adventure perspective, youâ€™ll find two major types of destinations. The first ones are the most popular ones which often are the most accessible and will have huge number of trekkers in seasons. These destinations often have a long history of exploration and something of global sensation what make them popular every year. These destinations include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Everest Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Sanctuary Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Dolpo Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Langtang Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Manaslu Circuit Trek, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Then, there are these other groups of destinations which are not as popular but offer an unmatched level of serenity, peace and wilderness that is hardly found anywhere. They offer the true sense of adventure, experience and the thrill of exploration. These destinations in Nepal include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Ruby Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tamang Heritage Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Api Himal Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">The Great Himalayan Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Makalu Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sherpini Col Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Kanchenjunga Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dhaulagiri Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sisne Himal Trek, and so on.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The choice of your destination depends on your time, cost, and the experience you wish to have.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-20 18:46:14');
INSERT INTO `cl_cost_includes` (`id`, `trip_detail_id`, `title`, `content`, `thumbnail`, `country`, `video`, `ordering`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1297, 147, 'EMERGENCY CONTACTS  & SAFETY', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you a mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travelers: Nepal is safe for solo travelers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>SIM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. Internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Emergency Numbers:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-20 18:46:14'),
(1298, 147, 'FOOD AND ACCOMMODATION', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Food (meal plan) and accommodation are among the most important things when in Nepal and in course of the trek. Please make sure to let the booking agency know of your allergies if you have any and also let them know if you are in any personal medication and need special attention at any time during the trek.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Accommodation in Kathmandu and Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Hotel Standards â€“ Most trekkers stay in 2-3 star hotels in Thamel (Kathmandu) or Lakeside (Pokhara) before and after trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Twin-Sharing Basis â€“ Standard bookings are twin-sharing, but single rooms can be arranged at an extra cost.</li>\r\n<li>Facilities â€“ Hotels offer hot showers, Wi-Fi, laundry services, and 24-hour electricity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Accommodation in Trekking Regions</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Teahouses / Lodges â€“ These are family-run guesthouses with dorm-style or twin rooms.</li>\r\n<li>Basic Bedding â€“ Rooms have wooden beds, foam mattresses, blankets, and pillows, but heating is not available in most lodges.</li>\r\n<li>Shared Bathrooms â€“ Most lodges have shared toilets and limited hot water (solar-heated in some places).</li>\r\n<li>Dining Areas â€“ Warm communal dining halls serve as social hubs for trekkers.</li>\r\n<li>Electricity &amp; Wi-Fi â€“ Available in lower-altitude teahouses but may require extra charges at higher altitudes.</li>\r\n<li>No Single Rooms at Higher Altitudes â€“ In remote areas, multi-bedded rooms may be the only option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Meals in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast &amp; Dinner â€“ Served at hotels or local restaurants.</li>\r\n<li>Wide Food Selection â€“ Includes Nepali, Indian, Chinese, and Western cuisine.</li>\r\n<li>Popular Dishes â€“ Dal Bhat (lentils &amp; rice), Momos (dumplings), Thukpa (Tibetan noodle soup), pizza, pasta, curries, and grilled meats.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Meals During Trekking</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Standard Trekking Meal Plan â€“ Breakfast, lunch, and dinner included in most trekking packages.</li>\r\n<li>Dining at Lodges â€“ Meals are prepared in teahouse kitchens, with all trekkers typically eating the same menu.</li>\r\n<li>Ordering in Advance â€“ Due to limited supplies in remote areas, meals must be ordered in advance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Common Meals on Treks</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast: porridge, pancakes, Tibetan bread, chapati, eggs, tea/coffee.</li>\r\n<li>Lunch &amp; Dinner: Dal Bhat (lentil soup, rice, vegetables), noodles, pasta, potatoes, soups, and curries.</li>\r\n<li>Vegetarian Options Available: Meat is available at lower altitudes but not recommended at high altitudes due to storage concerns.</li>\r\n<li>Soup &amp; Hydration: Garlic soup is often recommended as it helps with acclimatization.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Water &amp; Hydration</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Drinking Water Safety â€“ Tap water is not safe for drinking in Nepal.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Filtered/Boiled Water Provided â€“ Teahouses offer boiled or filtered water (often at extra cost).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Water Purification Recommended â€“ Trekkers should bring purification tablets, LifeStraw, or Water-to-Go bottles.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Avoid Plastic Bottles â€“ Buying bottled water is expensive and environmentally harmful.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 10, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-10-16 17:37:45'),
(1299, 147, 'ALTITUDE SICKNESS', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Altitude sickness, also known as Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS), occurs when the body fails to adapt to lower oxygen levels at high altitudes. It typically affects trekkers above 2,500 meters (8,200 ft) and can range from mild discomfort to life-threatening conditions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are different types of altitude sickness. AMS is the most common and is the first stage in getting altitude sickness. AMS if left unchecked goes on to become dangerous.</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p><strong>Type</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p><strong>Symptoms</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p><strong>Altitude Range</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p><strong>Severity</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Headache, nausea, dizziness, fatigue, loss of appetite, difficulty sleeping</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>2,500m â€“ 5,500m (8,200ft â€“ 18,000ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Mild to Moderate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Shortness of breath, persistent cough (frothy sputum), chest tightness, blue lips/nails</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 3,500m (11,500ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Severe &amp; Life-Threatening</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Cerebral Edema (HACE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Confusion, loss of coordination (ataxia), severe headache, unconsciousness</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 4,000m (13,100ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Fatal if Untreated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%;\">Note: HAPE and HACE are medical emergencies that require immediate descent and oxygen treatment</span></strong></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 11, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-20 18:46:14'),
(1300, 147, 'Altitude Sickness Risks', '<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â Â Rapid Ascent â€“ Climbing too quickly without proper acclimatization.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Genetic Susceptibility â€“ Some individuals are naturally more prone.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Dehydration &amp; Overexertion â€“ Increases symptoms of AMS.Â </li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Â  Previous History of AMS â€“ Higher risk if experienced before.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-10-16 17:37:45'),
(1301, 147, 'PREVENTION AND STRATEGIES', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>1. Follow the \"Golden Rule\" â€“ Climb High, Sleep Low</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Never ascend more than 500m (1,640ft) per day above 3,000m Or simply, follow your guide</li>\r\n<li>Every 1,000m (3,280ft) gain, take a rest/acclimatization day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>2. Stay Hydrated &amp; Maintain Nutrition</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Drink 3-4 liters of water daily to avoid dehydration.</li>\r\n<li>Eat carbohydrate-rich meals to sustain energy levels.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>3. Avoid Alcohol &amp; Sleeping Pills</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Alcohol dehydrates and worsens oxygen absorption.</li>\r\n<li>Sleeping pills suppress breathing and can increase AMS risk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>4. Use Acclimatization Stops</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp Trek: Acclimatization at Namche Bazaar (3,440m) &amp; Dingboche (4,410m).Â Â Annapurna Circuit: Rest at Manang (3,540m) before crossing Thorong La Â </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>5. Medication (For High-Risk Trekkers)Â Â Â </strong>Â Â Â Â </p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Diamox (Acetazolamide) â€“ Helps prevent AMS; start 125-250mg twice daily before ascent.</li>\r\n<li>Dexamethasone â€“ Emergency treatment for severe altitude sickness.</li>\r\n<li>Nifedipine â€“ Used for HAPE cases.</li>\r\n<li>Please note that these medicines require a medical professionalâ€™s prescription and canâ€™t be consumed haphazardly. Â  Â  Â </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>6. Descend Immediately if Symptoms Worsen</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If mild AMS symptoms persist, descend at least 300m (1,000ft).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If HAPE or HACE symptoms occur, descend immediately with medical help.Â Emergency Treatment &amp; Evacuation in Nepal</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Supplemental Oxygen â€“ Available in some lodges and hospitals.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gamow Bag (Portable Altitude Chamber) â€“ Used in extreme cases.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Helicopter Evacuation â€“ Costs $5,000 â€“ $10,000 USD (covered by good insurance).</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 13, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1302, 147, 'TRAVEL ADVISORY FOR NEPAL', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Travel Advisory for Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Before travelling to Nepal, it\'s important to stay informed about safety, health and entry requirements. Below is a detailed travel advisory covering safety, health guidelines, political stability and essential travel tips.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Health &amp; Vaccinations</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Required Vaccines: No mandatory vaccines for entry, but the following are recommended:</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Hepatitis A &amp; B â€“ Due to potentially contaminated food or water.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Typhoid â€“ For protectionÂ against foodborne illnesses.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Rabies â€“ If planning extended stays in remote areas.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tetanus &amp; Diphtheria â€“ Basic precaution.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Malaria &amp; Dengue: Malaria risk is low in Nepalâ€™s trekking regions but present in southern Terai areas (Chitwan, Lumbini).</li>\r\n<li>Dengue outbreaks occur seasonally (especially during the monsoon). Use mosquito repellent and wear long sleeves in affected areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Political Stability &amp; Security</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>General Safety: Nepal is politically stable and safe for travellers.</li>\r\n<li>Border Security: Certain trekking areas (e.g., Upper Mustang, Manaslu) require special permits. Travel to remote border regions (Tibet, India) may be restricted without prior approval.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travellers: Nepal is safe for solo travellers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">IM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. The internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Emergency Numbers:</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 14, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-19 18:39:48'),
(1303, 147, 'ABOUT NEPAL', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nestled between India and China, Nepal is a beautiful landlocked nation in South Asia. Nepal is renowned for having the highest mountain in the world, Mount Everest, and for its amazing Himalayan scenery, rich cultural legacy and friendly people. Lord Buddha was born there, and it\'s a popular destination for hikers, climbers and adventurers. A vibrant and spiritual destination, Nepal is remarkably diversified in terms of race, language and religion despite its tiny size.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Total Population of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As of 2025, Nepal has a population of approximately 31.5 million people.<br>The population is diverse, with over 100 ethnic groups and languages.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Nepalis Working Abroad</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Roughly 15â€“20% of Nepalâ€™s population is working overseas, mostly in countries like India, Malaysia, Qatar, UAE, and Saudi Arabia.<br>Remittances from these workers make up about 20â€“25% of the national GDP, making it a major part of the economy.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Condition of Youth in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Many youths are unemployed or underemployed, even after getting a degree.<br>Due to limited job opportunities and political instability, a significant number choose to migrate abroad for work.<br>Despite challenges, Nepali youth are resilient, talented and active in fields like tech, tourism, and entrepreneurship.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Current Condition of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal is a developing country with immense natural beauty and potential, especially in tourism and hydropower.<br>Major challenges include poverty, unemployment, infrastructure issues, and a high dependency on foreign aid and remittance.<br>Thereâ€™s a growing urban-rural gap, and many remote areas still lack basic services. Â  Â  Â Â </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Political Situation</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nepal is a federal democratic republic, but its political landscape is often unstable and fragmented. Frequent changes in government, internal party conflicts and a lack of long-term vision have slowed national progress.<br>Citizens are hopeful for better leadership and accountability, especially from the younger generation of politicians.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 15, 1, '2025-08-19 16:28:20', '2025-08-21 16:05:12'),
(1304, 260, 'WHAT\'S INCLUDED', '<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Ground travel as specified in the programme.</li>\r\n<li>Domestic flights as described.</li>\r\n<li>Accommodation as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li>Hotel as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li>Meals as described in the programme.</li>\r\n<li>Entrance fee to Annapurna Park.</li>\r\n<li>Professional guide</li>\r\n<li>Assistance from a local team during the trek.</li>\r\n<li>A first aid kit.</li>\r\n<li>1 porter for 2 clients</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1305, 260, 'WHAT\'S NOT INCLUDED', '<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\" type=\"disc\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Travel Insurance</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">International flight</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tips for porters and other trek staff</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"FR\">Drinks, souvenirs, Wifi internet, etc.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Anything not listed under \" price includes\"</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-10-16 19:18:51'),
(1306, 260, 'PERSONAL EXPENSES', '<p>Trekking in Nepal includes most major costs, but PERSONAL EXPENSES vary depending on individual spending habits. On average, â‚¬200 ($200-250 USD) should cover:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Beverages â€“ Soft drinks, tea, coffee, and alcoholic drinks (prices increase with altitude).</li>\r\n<li>Snacks &amp; Extras â€“ Chocolates, energy bars, and personal food purchases along the trek.</li>\r\n<li>Souvenirs â€“ Handicrafts, prayer flags, and traditional items from trekking villages.</li>\r\n<li>Tips for Guides &amp; Porters â€“ Tipping is customary in Nepal; recommended $5-$10 per day for guides and $3-$5 for porters.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1307, 260, 'CURRENCY & PAYMENT', '<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Accepted Currencies â€“ Nepali Rupees (NPR), US Dollars (USD), Euros (EUR), and British Pounds (GBP) are widely accepted.</li>\r\n<li>ATMs &amp; Card Payments â€“ Available in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara, but limited in trekking areas. Carry cash for mountain regions.</li>\r\n<li>Higher Prices at Altitude â€“ Expect higher costs as supplies are carried up manually or by yaks.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1308, 260, 'TIPS AND GRATITUDE', '<p>Tipping is a long-standing tradition in the adventure sector in Nepal and a meaningful way to show appreciation for the hard work of guides, porters, and trekking staff. While not mandatory, it is customary to tip at the end of the trek, usually as a group, to ensure a fair and organised distribution. Your trek guide will advise on an appropriate amount based on the trek duration and team size. Many groups present tips with a small farewell gathering or celebration on the last evening, marking the end of their trek. Additionally, trekkers often choose to donate equipment such as boots, gloves, hats, scarves, and trekking poles to the porters and crew. These items are highly valued and appreciated, especially by those working in the mountains. Tour leaders can be tipped separately during the final group dinner in Kathmandu or Pokhara. Though not obligatory, a small personal token of gratitude for their efforts enhances the spirit of mutual respect and appreciation.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-08-21 14:04:29'),
(1309, 260, 'BEST TIME TO BEST NEPAL', '<p>Frankly, Nepal is an all-season tourism destination. However, for adventure enthusiasts, there are 2 major seasons to visit Nepal. Here is a detailed look at the seasons and their weather patterns in Nepal for you to decide when best to visit:</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p><strong>Season</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p><strong>Months</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p><strong>Weather Characteristics</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p><strong>Trekking Conditions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Spring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>March â€“ May</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Mild temperatures, clear skies, blooming rhododendrons</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Excellent for trekking, colorful landscapes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Summer/ Monsoon</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>June â€“ August</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Heavy rainfall, humid, cloudy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Difficult due to slippery trails and poor visibility</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Autumn</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>September â€“ November</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Stable weather, clear skies, moderate temperatures</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Best season for trekking, peak tourist time</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"83\">\r\n<p>Winter</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"90\">\r\n<p>December â€“ February</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"168\">\r\n<p>Cold temperatures, snowfall at high altitudes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Suitable for lower-altitude treks, high passes may be closed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:43', '2025-08-21 14:04:29'),
(1310, 260, 'WEATHER CONDIDTION IN  NEPAL', '<p><strong>Spring season (March - May)Â </strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 30Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â <strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Stable weather, clear mornings, occasional afternoon clouds.</li>\r\n<li>Flowers and rhododendrons bloom, making the trails scenic.</li>\r\n<li>Increasing humidity in late May, signaling the approaching monsoon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â <strong>Best Treks for Spring:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp (EBC) Trek â€“ Best visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Annapurna Circuit â€“ Lush landscapes and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Langtang Valley Trek â€“ Ideal for nature lovers with vibrant forests.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Summer/Monsoon (June â€“ August)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 20Â°C â€“ 35Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: 0Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Heavy rainfall (average 200â€“500mm per month), especially in July and August.</li>\r\n<li>Frequent landslides and flight cancellations, especially in hilly areas.</li>\r\n<li>Leeches on lower-altitude trails due to humidity.</li>\r\n<li>Best Treks for Summer: (Only in rain-shadow areas with minimal rainfall)</li>\r\n<li>Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from monsoon.</li>\r\n<li>Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Autumn (September â€“ November) â€“ Best Trekking Season</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 10Â°C â€“ 28Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -5Â°C â€“ 15Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Stable weather, crystal-clear skies, and moderate temperatures.</li>\r\n<li>Best visibility of Himalayan peaks, making it the most popular season.</li>\r\n<li>Crowded trekking trails, especially on Everest Base Camp and Annapurna Circuit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Best Treks for Autumn:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp Trek â€“ Peak visibility of Everest.</li>\r\n<li>Manaslu Circuit Trek â€“ Challenging but scenic and less crowded.</li>\r\n<li>Gokyo Lakes Trek â€“ Stunning turquoise glacial lakes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Winter (December â€“ February)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Average Temperature:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara: 2Â°C â€“ 20Â°C</li>\r\n<li>Everest Base Camp &amp; Annapurna Base Camp: -15Â°C â€“ 10Â°C</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Weather &amp; Conditions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Cold temperatures, snowfall at higher elevations.</li>\r\n<li>Shorter daylight hours, some high passes (e.g., Thorong La) may be closed.</li>\r\n<li>Fewer trekkers, offering solitude.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Best Treks for Winter: (Lower-altitude treks to avoid extreme cold)</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Ghorepani Poon Hill Trek â€“ Short, scenic trek with snow-capped views.</li>\r\n<li>Everest Panorama Trek â€“ Lower-altitude trek with Everest views.</li>\r\n<li>Helambu Trek â€“ Close to Kathmandu, no high passes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1311, 260, 'BEST TREK & DESTINATION', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>In summer</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek â€“ Lies behind the Himalayas, shielded from the monsoon.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dolpo Trek â€“ Dry, high-altitude desert with unique Tibetan culture.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Best destination in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">This is tough to say because every destination in Nepal is a wonder on itself. Broadly, from adventure perspective, youâ€™ll find two major types of destinations. The first ones are the most popular ones which often are the most accessible and will have huge number of trekkers in seasons. These destinations often have a long history of exploration and something of global sensation what make them popular every year. These destinations include:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"uk-highlight uk-margin-top uk-margin-bottom\">\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Everest Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Annapurna Sanctuary Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Mustang Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Upper Dolpo Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Langtang Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Manaslu Circuit Trek, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Then, there are these other groups of destinations which are not as popular but offer an unmatched level of serenity, peace and wilderness that is hardly found anywhere. They offer the true sense of adventure, experience and the thrill of exploration. These destinations in Nepal include:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"uk-highlight uk-margin-top uk-margin-bottom\">\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Ruby Valley Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tamang Heritage Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Api Himal Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">The Great Himalayan Trail</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Makalu Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sherpini Col Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Kanchenjunga Base Camp Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Dhaulagiri Circuit Trek</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Sisne Himal Trek, and so on.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The choice of your destination depends on your time, cost, and the experience you wish to have.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1312, 260, 'EMMERGENCY CONTACT AND SAFETY', '<p><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you a mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travelers: Nepal is safe for solo travelers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>SIM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. Internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Emergency Numbers:</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li>General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li>Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li>Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1313, 260, 'FOOD & ACCCOMMODATION', '<p>Food (meal plan) and accommodation are among the most important things when in Nepal and in course of the trek. Please make sure to let the booking agency know of your allergies if you have any and also let them know if you are in any personal medication and need special attention at any time during the trek.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Accommodation in Kathmandu and Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hotel Standards â€“ Most trekkers stay in 2-3 star hotels in Thamel (Kathmandu) or Lakeside (Pokhara) before and after trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Twin-Sharing Basis â€“ Standard bookings are twin-sharing, but single rooms can be arranged at an extra cost.</li>\r\n<li>Facilities â€“ Hotels offer hot showers, Wi-Fi, laundry services, and 24-hour electricity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Accommodation in Trekking Regions</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Teahouses / Lodges â€“ These are family-run guesthouses with dorm-style or twin rooms.</li>\r\n<li>Basic Bedding â€“ Rooms have wooden beds, foam mattresses, blankets, and pillows, but heating is not available in most lodges.</li>\r\n<li>Shared Bathrooms â€“ Most lodges have shared toilets and limited hot water (solar-heated in some places).</li>\r\n<li>Dining Areas â€“ Warm communal dining halls serve as social hubs for trekkers.</li>\r\n<li>Electricity &amp; Wi-Fi â€“ Available in lower-altitude teahouses but may require extra charges at higher altitudes.</li>\r\n<li>No Single Rooms at Higher Altitudes â€“ In remote areas, multi-bedded rooms may be the only option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Meals in Kathmandu &amp; Pokhara</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast &amp; Dinner â€“ Served at hotels or local restaurants.</li>\r\n<li>Wide Food Selection â€“ Includes Nepali, Indian, Chinese, and Western cuisine.</li>\r\n<li>Popular Dishes â€“ Dal Bhat (lentils &amp; rice), Momos (dumplings), Thukpa (Tibetan noodle soup), pizza, pasta, curries, and grilled meats.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Meals During Trekking</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Standard Trekking Meal Plan â€“ Breakfast, lunch, and dinner included in most trekking packages.</li>\r\n<li>Dining at Lodges â€“ Meals are prepared in teahouse kitchens, with all trekkers typically eating the same menu.</li>\r\n<li>Ordering in Advance â€“ Due to limited supplies in remote areas, meals must be ordered in advance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Common Meals on Treks</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Breakfast: porridge, pancakes, Tibetan bread, chapati, eggs, tea/coffee.</li>\r\n<li>Lunch &amp; Dinner: Dal Bhat (lentil soup, rice, vegetables), noodles, pasta, potatoes, soups, and curries.</li>\r\n<li>Vegetarian Options Available: Meat is available at lower altitudes but not recommended at high altitudes due to storage concerns.</li>\r\n<li>Soup &amp; Hydration: Garlic soup is often recommended as it helps with acclimatization.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Water &amp; Hydration</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Drinking Water Safety â€“ Tap water is not safe for drinking in Nepal.</li>\r\n<li>Filtered/Boiled Water Provided â€“ Teahouses offer boiled or filtered water (often at extra cost).</li>\r\n<li>Water Purification Recommended â€“ Trekkers should bring purification tablets, LifeStraw, or Water-to-Go bottles.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid Plastic Bottles â€“ Buying bottled water is expensive and environmentally harmful.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 10, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-10-16 19:18:51'),
(1314, 260, 'ALTITUDE SICKNESS', '<p>Altitude sickness, also known as Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS), occurs when the body fails to adapt to lower oxygen levels at high altitudes. It typically affects trekkers above 2,500 meters (8,200 ft) and can range from mild discomfort to life-threatening conditions.</p>\r\n<p>There are different types of altitude sickness. AMS is the most common and is the first stage in getting altitude sickness. AMS if left unchecked goes on to become dangerous</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9505%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"><col style=\"width: 25.0132%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p><strong>Type</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p><strong>Symptoms</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p><strong>Altitude Range</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p><strong>Severity</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Headache, nausea, dizziness, fatigue, loss of appetite, difficulty sleeping</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>2,500m â€“ 5,500m (8,200ft â€“ 18,000ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Mild to Moderate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Pulmonary Edema (HAPE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Shortness of breath, persistent cough (frothy sputum), chest tightness, blue lips/nails</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 3,500m (11,500ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Severe &amp; Life-Threatening</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"114\">\r\n<p>High Altitude Cerebral Edema (HACE)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"204\">\r\n<p>Confusion, loss of coordination (ataxia), severe headache, unconsciousness</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"120\">\r\n<p>Above 4,000m (13,100ft)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"bottom\" width=\"100\">\r\n<p>Fatal if Untreated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><strong><span style=\"mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin; color: #363535; mso-font-kerning: 0pt; mso-bidi-language: NE;\">Note</span></strong><span style=\"mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'; mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin; color: #363535; mso-font-kerning: 0pt; mso-bidi-language: NE;\">:Â <strong>HAPE and HACE</strong>Â are medical emergencies that require immediate descent and oxygen treatment.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\">Â </p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 11, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:04:29'),
(1315, 260, 'ALTITUDE SICKNESS RISKS', '<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Â  Rapid Ascent â€“ Climbing too quickly without proper acclimatization.</li>\r\n<li>Â  Genetic Susceptibility â€“ Some individuals are naturally more prone.</li>\r\n<li>Â  Dehydration &amp; Overexertion â€“ Increases symptoms of AMS.Â </li>\r\n<li>Â  Previous History of AMS â€“ Higher risk if experienced before.</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-10-16 19:18:51'),
(1316, 260, 'PREVENTION & STRATEGIES', '<p><strong>1. Follow the \"Golden Rule\" â€“ Climb High, Sleep Low</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Never ascend more than 500m (1,640ft) per day above 3,000m Or simply, follow your guide</li>\r\n<li>Every 1,000m (3,280ft) gain, take a rest/acclimatization day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>2. Stay Hydrated &amp; Maintain Nutrition</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Â Drink 3-4 liters of water daily to avoid dehydration.</li>\r\n<li>Â Eat carbohydrate-rich meals to sustain energy levels</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>.<strong>3. Avoid Alcohol &amp; Sleeping Pills</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Alcohol dehydrates and worsens oxygen absorption.</li>\r\n<li>Sleeping pills suppress breathing and can increase AMS risk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>4. Use Acclimatization Stops</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Â Everest Base Camp Trek: Acclimatization at Namche Bazaar (3,440m) &amp; Dingboche (4,410m).Â Â Annapurna Circuit: Rest at Manang (3,540m) before crossing Thorong La Â </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>5. Medication (For High-Risk Trekkers)Â Â Â </strong>Â Â Â Â </p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Â Diamox (Acetazolamide) â€“ Helps prevent AMS; start 125-250mg twice daily before ascent.</li>\r\n<li>Â Dexamethasone â€“ Emergency treatment for severe altitude sickness.</li>\r\n<li>Â Nifedipine â€“ Used for HAPE cases.</li>\r\n<li>Â Please note that these medicines require a medical professionalâ€™s prescription and canâ€™t be consumed haphazardly. Â  Â  Â </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>6. Descend Immediately if Symptoms Worsen</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>If mild AMS symptoms persist, descend at least 300m (1,000ft).</li>\r\n<li>Â If HAPE or HACE symptoms occur, descend immediately with medical help.</li>\r\n<li>Â Emergency Treatment &amp; Evacuation in Nepal</li>\r\n<li>Â Supplemental Oxygen â€“ Available in some lodges and hospitals.</li>\r\n<li>Â Gamow Bag (Portable Altitude Chamber) â€“ Used in extreme cases.</li>\r\n<li>Â Helicopter Evacuation â€“ Costs $5,000 â€“ $10,000 USD (covered by good insurance).</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 13, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1317, 260, 'TRAVEL ADVISORY FOR NEPAL', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Travel Advisory for Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Before travelling to Nepal, it\'s important to stay informed about safety, health and entry requirements. Below is a detailed travel advisory covering safety, health guidelines, political stability and essential travel tips.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Health &amp; Vaccinations</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Required Vaccines: No mandatory vaccines for entry, but the following are recommended:</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Hepatitis A &amp; B â€“ Due to potentially contaminated food or water.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Typhoid â€“ For protectionÂ against foodborne illnesses.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Rabies â€“ If planning extended stays in remote areas.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Tetanus &amp; Diphtheria â€“ Basic precaution.</li>\r\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Malaria &amp; Dengue: Malaria risk is low in Nepalâ€™s trekking regions but present in southern Terai areas (Chitwan, Lumbini).</li>\r\n<li>Dengue outbreaks occur seasonally (especially during the monsoon). Use mosquito repellent and wear long sleeves in affected areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Political Stability &amp; Security</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>General Safety: Nepal is politically stable and safe for travellers.</li>\r\n<li>Border Security: Certain trekking areas (e.g., Upper Mustang, Manaslu) require special permits. Travel to remote border regions (Tibet, India) may be restricted without prior approval.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Natural Hazards &amp; Trekking Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Earthquakes: Nepal lies in a seismically active zone. Follow emergency protocols in case of tremors.</li>\r\n<li>Landslides &amp; Flooding: Monsoon season (Juneâ€“August) increases risks of landslides and road blockages. Trekkers should avoid landslide-prone areas and check the weather forecast before trekking.</li>\r\n<li>Avalanches &amp; Glacial Lake Outbursts: Winter and spring treks in high-altitude areas (Everest, Annapurna, Manaslu) may be affected. Hiring an experienced guide is strongly recommended. Our guides are well trained in avalanche safety and glacial hazards.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Crime &amp; Personal Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Crime Rate: Nepal has a low crime rate, but petty theft and scams exist.</li>\r\n<li>Common Scams: Overpriced taxis â€“ Always negotiate fares or use ride-hailing apps.</li>\r\n<li>Fake trekking permits â€“ Only book with registered trekking agencies. Booking with us gives you mental relief.</li>\r\n<li>Donation fraud â€“ Verify NGOs before donating.</li>\r\n<li>Solo Travellers: Nepal is safe for solo travellers, including women, but trekking alone is not recommended in remote areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Transportation Safety</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>Domestic Flights: Mountain weather can cause delays in flights to Lukla, Jomsom, and Pokhara. Book flexible return tickets in case of cancellations.</li>\r\n<li>Road Travel: Roads in Nepal are poorly maintained, and bus travel can be dangerous. Hiring a private vehicle with a driver is the safest option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Communication &amp; Emergency Contacts</strong></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>IM Cards &amp; Internet: NCELL and Nepal Telecom (NTC) offer prepaid SIM cards for tourists. The internet is available in major cities but can be unreliable in remote trekking areas.</li>\r\n<li>Emergency Numbers:</li>\r\n<li>Tourist Police: 1144</li>\r\n<li>General Police: 100</li>\r\n<li>Ambulance: 102</li>\r\n<li>Nepal Immigration Office: +977 1-4113045</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 14, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42'),
(1318, 260, 'ABOUT NEPAL', '<p>Nestled between India and China, Nepal is a beautiful landlocked nation in South Asia. Nepal is renowned for having the highest mountain in the world, Mount Everest, and for its amazing Himalayan scenery, rich cultural legacy and friendly people. Lord Buddha was born there, and it\'s a popular destination for hikers, climbers and adventurers. A vibrant and spiritual destination, Nepal is remarkably diversified in terms of race, language and religion despite its tiny size.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Total Population of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p>As of 2025, Nepal has a population of approximately 31.5 million people.<br>The population is diverse, with over 100 ethnic groups and languages.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Nepalis Working Abroad</strong></p>\r\n<p>Roughly 15â€“20% of Nepalâ€™s population is working overseas, mostly in countries like India, Malaysia, Qatar, UAE, and Saudi Arabia.<br>Remittances from these workers make up about 20â€“25% of the national GDP, making it a major part of the economy.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Condition of Youth in Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p>Many youths are unemployed or underemployed, even after getting a degree.<br>Due to limited job opportunities and political instability, a significant number choose to migrate abroad for work.<br>Despite challenges, Nepali youth are resilient, talented and active in fields like tech, tourism, and entrepreneurship.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Current Condition of Nepal</strong></p>\r\n<p>Nepal is a developing country with immense natural beauty and potential, especially in tourism and hydropower.<br>Major challenges include poverty, unemployment, infrastructure issues, and a high dependency on foreign aid and remittance.<br>Thereâ€™s a growing urban-rural gap, and many remote areas still lack basic services. Â  Â  Â Â </p>\r\n<p><strong>Political Situation</strong></p>\r\n<p>Nepal is a federal democratic republic, but its political landscape is often unstable and fragmented. Frequent changes in government, internal party conflicts and a lack of long-term vision have slowed national progress.<br>Citizens are hopeful for better leadership and accountability, especially from the younger generation of politicians.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 15, 1, '2025-08-21 13:52:44', '2025-08-21 14:31:42');
